const EYELOG_QUESTIONS = [
// ── OPTICS & REFRACTION ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'op01',subject:'optics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient has a spectacle prescription of -3.00 +1.50 x 090. What is the power of this lens in the 180° meridian?',
options:['A. -3.00 D','B. -1.50 D','C. +1.50 D','D. -4.50 D','E. 0.00 D'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'In the 090 meridian the lens power is -3.00 D (sphere). In the 180 meridian the cylinder is added: -3.00 + 1.50 = -1.50 D. Remember: the cylinder axis indicates the meridian where NO cylinder power is added; the full cylinder is added 90° away.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op02',subject:'optics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'A vergence of +2.00 D means light rays are:',
options:['A. Diverging from a point 50 cm away','B. Converging to a point 50 cm away','C. Parallel','D. Diverging from a point 2 m away','E. Converging to a point 2 m away'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Vergence = 1 / distance (in metres). +2.00 D means converging (+) light headed to a focus 1/2 = 0.50 m (50 cm) ahead.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op03',subject:'optics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'A patient wearing +10.00 D spectacles (vertex distance 14 mm) needs contact lenses. What contact lens power is needed?',
options:['A. +10.00 D','B. +8.70 D','C. +11.54 D','D. +9.00 D','E. +10.50 D'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Contact lens power = F_spec / (1 - d × F_spec) is for moving away. Correct: moving from spectacle to corneal plane (closer), plus power decreases. F_cl = F/(1+dF) = 10/(1+0.14) = 8.77 ≈ +8.70 D. Use the version where vertex distance correction for plus: contact = spec/(1+d×spec).',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op04',subject:'optics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The nodal point of the reduced schematic eye is located:',
options:['A. At the cornea','B. 17 mm behind the cornea','C. 7 mm behind the cornea','D. At the principal plane of the lens','E. At the retina'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'In the reduced schematic eye, the single refracting surface is placed at the cornea and the nodal point (where rays pass undeviated) is approximately 7 mm behind it — roughly at the posterior lens.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op05',subject:'optics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'A direct ophthalmoscope produces a:',
options:['A. Real, inverted image at 15×','B. Virtual, erect image at approximately 15×','C. Real, erect image at 2×','D. Virtual, inverted image at 15×','E. Real, inverted image at 2×'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The direct ophthalmoscope creates a virtual, erect (upright), magnified image (~15×). The observer\'s eye and the patient\'s eye together act as a compound microscope.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op06',subject:'optics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Which of the following best describes the lensometer (lensmeter) measurement principle?',
options:['A. It measures the vergence of light exiting a lens placed in front of a standard eye','B. It uses a Badal optometer: a standard lens creates parallel light from a known vergence target','C. It measures the curvature of each lens surface with a keratometer','D. It uses a Hartmann-Shack wavefront sensor','E. It measures total internal reflection angle to calculate refractive index'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The lensometer uses a Badal principle: a standard lens (the instrument objective) is placed at its focal length from the unknown lens. A target is moved until the exit light is parallel (neutralized), and the distance moved gives the lens power.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op07',subject:'optics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'A patient with keratoconus achieves 20/20 with a rigid gas-permeable (RGP) contact lens but only 20/100 with spectacles. The MOST likely reason is:',
options:['A. The contact lens corrects higher-order aberrations by creating a new anterior refracting surface','B. The contact lens magnifies the image more than spectacles','C. Spectacles cannot correct more than 10 D of myopia','D. Keratoconus affects only the posterior corneal surface which spectacles cannot address','E. The tear lens formed under an RGP neutralizes irregular astigmatism'],
correct:'E',
explanation:'In keratoconus, irregular astigmatism prevents good spectacle correction. An RGP lens vaults over the irregular cornea; the tear (lacrimal) lens formed between the back of the RGP and the cone fills in the irregularity, effectively replacing the irregular corneal surface with a smooth spherical interface. This is the primary mechanism, not higher-order aberration correction per se.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op08',subject:'optics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A +5.00 D thin lens has its object placed 25 cm in front of it. Where is the image?',
options:['A. 50 cm behind the lens','B. 100 cm behind the lens','C. 25 cm in front of the lens (virtual)','D. Infinity','E. 33 cm behind the lens'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Using 1/v - 1/u = P: object at u = -0.25 m, P = +5 D, f = 0.20 m. 1/v = 1/f + 1/u = 5 + (-4) = 1. So v = 1 m = 100 cm. Object at 25 cm from a +5 D lens (f=20 cm): since object is beyond f, image is real and at 100 cm behind the lens.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

// ── OPTICS (continued) ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'op09',subject:'optics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient with -6.00 D myopia has their far point at:',
options:['A. 6 m in front of the eye','B. 16.7 cm in front of the eye','C. 6 cm in front of the eye','D. Infinity','E. 16.7 m in front of the eye'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The far point is the object point conjugate to the retina when accommodation is relaxed. For a myope with -6.00 D: distance = 1/6 = 0.167 m = 16.7 cm in front of the eye. This is why -6 myopes can read without glasses at ~17 cm.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op10',subject:'optics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'A patient is fitted with a +10 D aphakic spectacle lens (vertex distance 12 mm). When they look through the peripheral edge of the lens, they experience a "jack-in-the-box" phenomenon. This is due to:',
options:['A. Chromatic aberration of the high-plus lens','B. Prismatic effect at the lens periphery causing objects to jump into and out of the field','C. Reduced contrast sensitivity from light scatter','D. Radial distortion from the steep lens curvature','E. Magnification mismatch between the two eyes'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'High-plus aphakic lenses have large prismatic effects at the periphery (Prentice\'s rule: P = F × d). Objects beyond the field of view through the lens are seen over the top/bottom of the lens without magnification. When the patient scans their gaze, objects "jump" into view through the lens with sudden magnification — the jack-in-the-box effect. Ring scotoma (the blind zone between direct and lens-aided view) is another consequence.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op11',subject:'optics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'In retinoscopy, the reflex moves WITH the motion of the light streak when:',
options:['A. The working distance lens has been added and the eye is neutralized','B. The patient is myopic and the retinoscope is beyond the far point','C. The patient is hyperopic or the retinoscope is inside the far point of a myope','D. The patient has irregular astigmatism','E. The reflex is always with motion regardless of refractive error'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'With motion (same as streak movement) occurs when the far point of the eye is behind the observer (hyperopia) or when the observer is inside the far point of a myope. Against motion occurs when the observer is outside the far point (myopia). Neutralization = reflex fills the pupil uniformly. Add a -1.50 D working distance lens to the net retinoscopy result (for 67 cm working distance).',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op12',subject:'optics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'A prism of 4 prism diopters placed base-out in front of the right eye will displace the image:',
options:['A. 4 cm at 1 m, toward the apex (nasally)','B. 4 cm at 1 m, toward the base (temporally)','C. 4 mm at 1 m, toward the apex','D. 4 cm at 100 cm, toward the base','E. No displacement — prisms only affect vergence'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'A prism deviates light toward its base and the image appears displaced toward the apex. 1 prism diopter displaces an image 1 cm at 1 m. So 4 PD base-out displaces the image 4 cm at 1 m toward the apex (nasally = toward the nose). The eye must converge (rotate in) to fuse, compensating for the base-out deviation.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op13',subject:'optics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Which formula is used to calculate the EFFECTIVE power of a lens when it is moved closer to the eye?',
options:['A. F_eff = F / (1 + d·F)','B. F_eff = F × (1 + d·F)','C. F_eff = F - d','D. F_eff = 1 / (f - d)','E. F_eff = F / (1 - d·F)'],
correct:'E',
explanation:'When a lens is moved closer to the eye (d decreases), the effective vergence changes. Moving a PLUS lens closer to the eye DECREASES its effective power: F_eff = F / (1 - d·F). Moving a MINUS lens closer increases its effective power (in magnitude). This is the basis of vertex distance correction: a strong plus spectacle lens moved from 14 mm to 0 mm (contact lens) loses power.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op14',subject:'optics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Keratometry measures the:',
options:['A. Total corneal power including posterior surface','B. Anterior corneal curvature using a calibrated mire-reflection technique, assuming a standard refractive index','C. Corneal thickness by reflection off the epithelium and endothelium','D. Corneal topography over the entire anterior surface','E. Posterior corneal radius of curvature'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Keratometry measures the anterior corneal surface curvature by measuring the size of reflected mires from two or four points ~3.2 mm from the visual axis. It uses a calibrated refractive index (n=1.3375) to convert radius (mm) to power (D). Importantly, it does NOT measure the posterior cornea and covers only the central ~3 mm. Topography measures a wider area but still only the anterior surface.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op15',subject:'optics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The Maddox rod test is used to:',
options:['A. Measure refractive error objectively','B. Dissociate the eyes to measure the full phoria or tropia','C. Detect early nuclear sclerosis','D. Measure the anterior chamber depth','E. Assess color vision deficiencies'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The Maddox rod converts a white point light into a red streak (by fusing multiple high-powered cylinder lenses). When placed in front of one eye, it dissociates fusion (the two eyes see completely different images) and allows measurement of the full heterophoria or tropia without fusional vergences compensating. The rod streak and dot light should be superimposed if no deviation is present.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op16',subject:'optics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A fundus contact lens with a power of +60 D is used to examine the retina. The image formed is:',
options:['A. Virtual, erect, magnified — at the posterior nodal point of the eye','B. Real, inverted, magnified — in the air in front of the lens','C. Real, erect, at the anterior surface of the lens','D. Virtual, inverted, 15× magnified','E. Real, inverted — at infinity'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'High-powered indirect condensing lenses (60 D, 78 D, 90 D) as slit-lamp fundus lenses form a real, inverted, aerial image of the fundus in the air between the lens and the observer. The observer then views this aerial image as if through a loupe. Magnification = 60/slit-lamp eyepiece. This contrasts with the direct ophthalmoscope (virtual, erect). The image is INVERTED (both up-down and left-right) with these lenses.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op17',subject:'optics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'A patient has 2.00 D of astigmatism with the steep axis at 090 (against-the-rule). To neutralize this with a cylinder, the axis of the correcting minus cylinder should be at:',
options:['A. 090','B. 180','C. 045','D. 135','E. It depends on the spherical equivalent'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Against-the-rule (ATR) astigmatism: the steep corneal meridian is at 090 (more power horizontally... wait, ATR = steep at 180, less power at 090). Let me reconsider. ATR: steep axis at 180 (horizontal). WTR: steep at 090 (vertical). The question states steep axis at 090 = WTR astigmatism. To correct with minus cylinder: the minus cylinder axis is placed AT the steep meridian. Steep at 090, so minus cyl axis at 090. This neutralizes the excess power at 090.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op18',subject:'optics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Transposition of -2.00 +3.00 × 045 yields:',
options:['A. +1.00 -3.00 × 135','B. +3.00 -3.00 × 090','C. +1.00 -3.00 × 045','D. -2.00 +3.00 × 135','E. +1.00 +3.00 × 045'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Transposition steps: (1) New sphere = algebraic sum of old sphere + cylinder: -2.00 + 3.00 = +1.00. (2) New cylinder = opposite sign of old cylinder: -3.00. (3) New axis = old axis ± 90°: 045 + 90 = 135. Result: +1.00 -3.00 × 135.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op19',subject:'optics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Duochrome (red-green, bichrome) test: a patient says letters on the RED side are sharper. This suggests:',
options:['A. Myopic over-correction (too much minus)','B. Hyperopic over-correction (too much plus)','C. Emmetropia — balanced endpoint','D. Color vision deficiency','E. Astigmatism along the horizontal axis'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Green light has a shorter wavelength and focuses slightly in front of red. In emmetropia (or correct refraction), the circle of least confusion falls on the retina and both sides look equally clear. If red is clearer, the focal point is behind the retina (hyperopia or under-minus) — add more minus. If green is clearer, the focal point is in front (myopia or over-minus) — add more plus. "Red = add minus; Green = add plus" is the clinical rule.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

{id:'op20',subject:'optics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The resolving power of the eye (minimum angle of resolution) under photopic conditions is approximately:',
options:['A. 1 arc second','B. 1 arc minute','C. 10 arc minutes','D. 0.1 arc seconds','E. 5 arc minutes'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Normal photopic visual acuity of 20/20 corresponds to a minimum angle of resolution (MAR) of 1 arc minute (1\'). Each letter on the 20/20 line subtends 5 arc minutes total, and the gap/stroke within the letter subtends 1 arc minute. This is the Snellen standard. The theoretical diffraction limit of the eye (~2 mm pupil) is about 1 arc minute, matching photoreceptor spacing at the foveola.',
reference:'BCSC Section 3'},

// ── CATARACT & LENS ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'ca01',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A 68-year-old diabetic undergoes uncomplicated phacoemulsification. Which intraocular lens (IOL) feature is MOST important to reduce posterior capsule opacification (PCO)?',
options:['A. Hydrophilic acrylic material','B. Square posterior optic edge','C. Large optic diameter (>7 mm)','D. Blue-light filtering chromophore','E. Plate haptic design'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The square (sharp/truncated) posterior optic edge creates a physical barrier at the optic-capsule interface that prevents lens epithelial cell migration onto the posterior capsule — the main mechanism of PCO. This is the single most important design feature for PCO reduction.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca02',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'During phacoemulsification, a posterior capsule tear is noted after hydrodissection but before nuclear disassembly. The BEST next step is:',
options:['A. Convert immediately to ECCE','B. Inject viscoelastic behind the nucleus to tamponade the tear, then proceed carefully','C. Place a capsular tension ring','D. Abandon the case and reschedule','E. Continue phaco normally as the tear is small'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Injecting a dispersive viscoelastic (e.g., Viscoat) behind the nuclear fragment supports the vitreous face and prevents extension of the tear. The surgeon can then proceed with careful phacoemulsification, ideally converting to a slower, lower-vacuum technique. Immediate ECCE conversion is an option if the tear is large, but controlled use of viscoelastic first is preferred.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca03',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Which formula is MOST accurate for short eyes (axial length <22 mm)?',
options:['A. SRK/T','B. Holladay 1','C. Barrett Universal II','D. SRK II','E. Hoffer Q'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'For short eyes (<22 mm), modern vergence formulas like Barrett Universal II, Hill-RBF, and Kane outperform older generation formulas. Hoffer Q was traditionally preferred for short eyes over SRK/T, but Barrett Universal II consistently shows lowest mean prediction error across all axial lengths including short eyes in recent large comparative studies.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca04',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient reports monocular diplopia after cataract surgery. Slit lamp shows the IOL optic straddling the anterior capsulorrhexis edge. The MOST likely cause of the diplopia is:',
options:['A. Induced irregular astigmatism','B. Edge glare from the haptic','C. Dysphotopsia from light passing around the IOL edge','D. Capsular contraction syndrome','E. Decentration causing prismatic effect'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'When the IOL optic edge is not fully covered by the capsulorrhexis (i.e., IOL-in-the-bag with edge exposed), light can difract around the IOL edge causing dysphotopsia — positive (bright arcs/flashes) or negative (dark arc in temporal field). Straddling the rhexis edge classically produces edge-related dysphotopsia.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca05',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The "no-reflow" phenomenon after capsular tension ring (CTR) placement refers to:',
options:['A. Failure of the capsule to re-expand after viscoelastic removal','B. Occlusion of the ciliary body blood supply during ring placement','C. Iris ischemia after prolonged pupil stretching','D. Choroidal non-perfusion seen after hypotony during vitreous loss','E. Fibrin formation blocking the trabecular meshwork postoperatively'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'No-reflow in cataract surgery context refers to failure of the posterior capsule to re-expand and come into contact with the IOL after removal of viscoelastic — typically seen with a CTR in the bag and improperly formed posterior capsule.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca06',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Posterior polar cataract is associated with increased risk of:',
options:['A. Zonular dialysis','B. Posterior capsule rupture during hydrodissection','C. Corneal decompensation','D. Suprachoroidal hemorrhage','E. Iris prolapse'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Posterior polar cataracts have a pre-existing defect or thinning of the posterior capsule at the polar opacity. Hydrodissection can cause a fluid wave that ruptures this weakened capsule. The key surgical modification is to perform hydrodelineation instead, and use extra care or skip hydrodissection entirely.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca07',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'A patient with a history of LASIK for myopia now needs cataract surgery. Which IOL calculation adjustment is MOST appropriate?',
options:['A. Add +0.50 D to the standard IOL power','B. Use the Clinical History Method or a corneal bypass formula','C. Rely on automated keratometry alone','D. Use the thinnest corneal zone for keratometry','E. Increase the A-constant by 1.0'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Post-refractive surgery eyes have altered anterior corneal curvature. Standard keratometry over-estimates corneal power (using a fixed index of refraction that no longer applies). The Clinical History Method (adjusting K with pre-LASIK data), Haigis-L, Barrett True-K, or the ASCRS post-refractive calculator are preferred. Never rely on standard automated keratometry alone.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca08',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Floppy iris syndrome (IFIS) is most commonly associated with which medication?',
options:['A. Tamsulosin (Flomax)','B. Metoprolol','C. Aspirin','D. Amlodipine','E. Sildenafil'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Intraoperative floppy iris syndrome (IFIS) is strongly associated with systemic alpha-1-adrenergic antagonists, especially tamsulosin (used for benign prostatic hyperplasia). The iris dilator muscle is blocked, leading to intraoperative iris billowing, prolapse, and progressive miosis. Surgeons must be warned preoperatively — the drug does not need to be stopped but technique modification (iris hooks, Malyugin ring, intracameral phenylephrine, low-flow phaco) is needed.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca09',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'In which situation is a toric IOL MOST likely to under-correct the astigmatism despite accurate preoperative planning?',
options:['A. Posterior corneal astigmatism exceeding +0.5 D in magnitude','B. With-the-rule astigmatism in a young patient','C. Posterior corneal astigmatism not accounted for in the calculation','D. IOL rotation of less than 5 degrees','E. Axial length >25 mm'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'The posterior cornea contributes approximately 0.3 D of against-the-rule astigmatism on average. Keratometers and topographers measure ANTERIOR corneal curvature only. If posterior corneal astigmatism is not accounted for (using Barrett Toric, Abulafia-Koch formula, or direct measurement by Scheimpflug/OCT), a toric IOL calculated from anterior K values alone will be systematically miscalculated.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

// ── CATARACT (continued) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'ca10',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The recommended treatment for visually significant nuclear sclerotic cataract in a 70-year-old otherwise healthy patient with 20/80 vision is:',
options:['A. Observation for 6 months then reassess','B. Phacoemulsification with IOL implantation','C. ECCE (extracapsular cataract extraction) only','D. Intracapsular cataract extraction','E. YAG laser capsulotomy'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Phacoemulsification with IOL implantation is the standard surgical treatment for visually significant cataract. Indications: vision affecting daily activities (driving, reading), glare, or functional impairment. YAG capsulotomy treats POSTERIOR capsule opacification (PCO) after cataract surgery, not the cataract itself. ICCE is obsolete in modern practice.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca11',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient develops a suprachoroidal hemorrhage (SCH) during phacoemulsification. The FIRST step is:',
options:['A. Complete the case as quickly as possible','B. Immediately close the wound to restore IOP and tamponade the hemorrhage','C. Convert to ECCE for better exposure','D. Inject intravitreal gas','E. Perform vitrectomy at the same sitting'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Suprachoroidal hemorrhage is an expulsive complication caused by choroidal artery rupture. Management: immediately close the wound (suture if needed) to restore positive IOP, which tamponades the bleeding. Do NOT continue phaco. Symptoms: sudden shallowing of AC, hardening of the eye, pain, iris/vitreous prolapse. Drain SCH electively 7-14 days later if non-resolving or causing RD.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca12',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Which phacoemulsification machine parameter MOST directly reduces the risk of posterior capsule rupture during nuclear sculpting?',
options:['A. High irrigation bottle height','B. Low vacuum / high flow (aspiration flow rate)','C. Low ultrasound power with burst mode or torsional US','D. High vacuum to hold nuclear fragments firmly','E. Increased infusion sleeve irrigation rate'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Lower ultrasound power reduces thermal and mechanical stress on the capsule. Torsional ultrasound (Ozil) cuts rather than pushing, reducing repulsion of lens material toward the capsule. High vacuum is efficient for holding but increases post-occlusion surge risk. High flow increases turbulence. Using the lowest effective US power with a dispersive viscoelastic on the capsule is key to preventing posterior capsule rupture.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca13',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Multifocal IOLs are CONTRAINDICATED in which patient?',
options:['A. A 60-year-old with bilateral visually significant nuclear cataracts','B. A patient with moderate dry AMD and reduced contrast sensitivity','C. A patient with mild astigmatism (<0.75 D) corrected with a toric IOL','D. A patient who previously wore reading glasses for 10 years','E. A patient who had prior LASIK for low myopia (-2.00 D)'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Multifocal IOLs split light into multiple focal points, reducing contrast sensitivity at each focus. They are contraindicated in any patient with reduced contrast sensitivity (AMD, glaucoma, corneal disease), irregular astigmatism, or occupations requiring high-quality mesopic vision (night drivers, pilots). Prior LASIK is a relative contraindication (IOL power calculation is less predictable, not the MF optics per se).',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca14',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Endophthalmitis after cataract surgery MOST commonly presents within:',
options:['A. 24-48 hours','B. 1 week (typically 3-7 days post-op)','C. 4-6 weeks','D. 3-6 months (delayed chronic form)','E. Within hours of surgery'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Acute post-operative endophthalmitis peaks at 3-7 days post-operatively, though it can occur within 24-48 hours to 6 weeks. The most common organism is Staphylococcus epidermidis (coagulase-negative staph, ~70%). The Endophthalmitis Vitrectomy Study (EVS) showed that vitreous tap + intravitreal antibiotics (vancomycin + amikacin or ceftazidime) is equivalent to PPV for light-perception-or-better vision; PPV is superior for hand-motion or worse vision.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca15',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Which of the following is the BEST description of a positive relative afferent pupillary defect (RAPD) in the setting of a dense cataract?',
options:['A. A dense cataract alone can cause a significant RAPD','B. RAPD is caused by cataract-induced retinal changes','C. A cataract does NOT cause a clinically significant RAPD; its presence suggests optic nerve or retinal disease','D. RAPD is expected after YAG capsulotomy','E. Only posterior subcapsular cataracts cause RAPD'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Media opacities (cataract, vitreous hemorrhage, corneal opacity) do NOT cause RAPD. The pupillary light reflex depends on the optic nerve, not on image quality. A positive RAPD in a cataract eye indicates concurrent optic nerve disease (optic neuritis, glaucoma, AION) or significant retinal disease. This is a critical preoperative finding — it predicts limited visual recovery from cataract surgery alone.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca16',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'The SRK/T formula performs poorly in which situation?',
options:['A. Average axial length (22-24 mm)','B. Very long eyes (>26 mm, high myopia)','C. Posterior chamber IOL','D. Sulcus-placed IOL','E. Eyes with prior angle-closure glaucoma'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'SRK/T systematically over-estimates corneal power (from keratometry) in very long, highly myopic eyes, leading to under-correction (hyperopic surprise). In long eyes, Barrett Universal II, Holladay 2, and Olsen formula perform better. For short eyes, Hoffer Q and Barrett Universal II are superior. The original SRK formula was a regression formula; SRK/T is a theoretical modification but still poorly handles extreme axial lengths.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca17',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Pseudoexfoliation (PXF) syndrome is associated with all of the following EXCEPT:',
options:['A. Increased risk of glaucoma','B. Systemic cardiovascular and cerebrovascular disease','C. Reduced corneal endothelial cell density','D. Autosomal dominant inheritance with complete penetrance','E. Unilateral presentation at onset (may become bilateral over time)'],
correct:'D',
explanation:'PXF syndrome is multifactorial, NOT a simple autosomal dominant condition with complete penetrance. While LOXL1 gene polymorphisms strongly associate with PXF risk, environmental factors contribute and penetrance is incomplete. PXF is associated with glaucoma (~5× risk), zonular weakness, corneal endothelial dysfunction, and systemic vascular disease. It is often unilateral at presentation but may become bilateral.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca18',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The most common type of cataract in patients over age 60 is:',
options:['A. Posterior subcapsular cataract','B. Anterior subcapsular cataract','C. Nuclear sclerotic cataract','D. Cortical cataract','E. Christmas tree (polychromatic) cataract'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Nuclear sclerotic cataract is the most common age-related cataract, caused by progressive compaction and oxidation of central lens fibers. It causes index myopia (patient notes improved near vision — "second sight"), color shift (brunescence), and increased spherical aberration. PSC cataracts are more common in younger patients, steroid users, and diabetics. Cortical cataracts are also common in diabetics.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca19',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'In the Endophthalmitis Vitrectomy Study (EVS), systemic antibiotics (IV cefazolin + amikacin) were shown to:',
options:['A. Significantly improve outcomes in all presentations','B. Improve outcomes when initial visual acuity was light perception or worse','C. Provide no benefit over vitreous tap/injection alone','D. Only benefit gram-positive endophthalmitis','E. Improve outcomes in delayed-onset endophthalmitis'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'The EVS showed that systemic antibiotics (IV cefazolin + amikacin) added NO benefit over intravitreal antibiotics alone in acute post-cataract endophthalmitis. The study also showed that immediate vitrectomy was superior to vitreous tap/injection only when initial vision was LP or worse. For HM or better vision, tap/injection was equivalent to PPV. Systemic antibiotics are no longer recommended for post-cataract endophthalmitis.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

{id:'ca20',subject:'cataract',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'A 45-year-old patient on long-term corticosteroids for rheumatoid arthritis develops a cataract. The MOST likely morphology is:',
options:['A. Nuclear sclerosis','B. Anterior subcapsular opacity','C. Posterior subcapsular cataract (PSC)','D. Cortical spoke opacity','E. Anterior polar cataract'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Corticosteroid-induced cataracts (systemic, topical ophthalmic, or inhaled) classically cause posterior subcapsular cataracts (PSC). Mechanism: steroids may induce oxidative stress in posterior subcapsular lens epithelial cells. PSC causes glare and near vision problems (the opacity is in the optical axis during accommodation). Other PSC associations: radiation, uveitis, trauma, diabetes, RP.',
reference:'BCSC Section 11'},

// ── CORNEA & EXTERNAL DISEASE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'co01',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'A 25-year-old contact lens wearer presents with a central corneal ulcer, hypopyon, and severe pain. Gram stain of the scraping shows gram-negative rods. The MOST likely organism is:',
options:['A. Staphylococcus aureus','B. Streptococcus pneumoniae','C. Pseudomonas aeruginosa','D. Acanthamoeba','E. Fusarium solani'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Pseudomonas aeruginosa is the most common gram-negative rod causing bacterial keratitis, especially in contact lens wearers. It produces rapid, aggressive stromal necrosis with a characteristic "ground-glass" opacification and mucopurulent discharge. Treatment: intensive topical fluoroquinolone (ciprofloxacin or moxifloxacin).',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co02',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Lattice corneal dystrophy type I (Biber-Haab-Dimmer) is caused by mutations in which gene?',
options:['A. TGFBI (transforming growth factor beta-induced)','B. SLC4A11','C. ZEB1','D. VSX1','E. COL8A2'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'TGFBI (formerly BIGH3) mutations cause multiple corneal stromal dystrophies depending on the specific mutation: Granular type I (R555W), Granular type II/Avellino (R124H), Lattice type I (R124C), and Reis-Bucklers (R124L). All are autosomal dominant. SLC4A11 causes CHED. ZEB1 causes Posterior polymorphous and CHED2. VSX1 causes Keratoconus. COL8A2 causes FECD.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co03',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient with recurrent corneal erosion syndrome reports waking at night with severe pain and tearing. The FIRST-LINE treatment after an acute episode has resolved is:',
options:['A. Phototherapeutic keratectomy (PTK)','B. Anterior stromal puncture','C. Hypertonic saline drops and lubricating ointment at bedtime','D. Bandage contact lens permanently','E. Corneal scraping and debridement'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'First-line management for recurrent corneal erosion syndrome (RCES) is lubricating ointment at bedtime and hypertonic saline (5% NaCl) drops during the day to reduce epithelial edema and strengthen epithelial adhesion. If this fails after 3-6 months, procedural options include anterior stromal puncture (for non-visual axis erosions), diamond burr polishing, or PTK.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co04',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Fuchs endothelial corneal dystrophy (FECD) most commonly results from trinucleotide repeat expansion in which gene?',
options:['A. COL8A2','B. TCF4 (transcription factor 4)','C. SLC4A11','D. LOXHD1','E. ZEB1'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The most common genetic cause of late-onset FECD (>95% of cases) is a CTG trinucleotide repeat expansion in intron 2 of TCF4. This creates nuclear RNA foci that sequester splicing factors. Early-onset FECD is caused by COL8A2 mutations (autosomal dominant). ZEB1 mutations cause posterior polymorphous dystrophy and CHED2.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co05',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Acanthamoeba keratitis is strongly associated with which risk factor?',
options:['A. HIV/AIDS','B. Soft contact lens wear with tap water exposure','C. Herpes simplex virus keratitis','D. Dry eye disease','E. Post-refractive surgery'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Acanthamoeba keratitis is overwhelmingly associated with contact lens wear, particularly exposure to contaminated water (tap water, swimming pools, hot tubs). The classic presentation is severe pain out of proportion to slit-lamp findings and a ring-shaped stromal infiltrate. Diagnosis: confocal microscopy, culture on non-nutrient agar with E. coli overlay.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co06',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Penetrating keratoplasty (PK) versus Descemet membrane endothelial keratoplasty (DMEK) for Fuchs dystrophy: which statement is MOST accurate?',
options:['A. PK provides faster visual recovery','B. DMEK has higher graft rejection rates than PK','C. DMEK provides better visual acuity outcomes and lower rejection rates','D. DMEK is preferred for eyes with significant anterior stromal scarring','E. PK and DMEK have equivalent refractive predictability'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'DMEK replaces only the diseased Descemet membrane and endothelium (the pathological layers in FECD). Advantages over PK: faster visual recovery (weeks vs months-years), better final BCVA (often 20/20+), dramatically lower rejection rates (~1% vs ~20%), no suture-related issues, less induced astigmatism. DMEK is NOT appropriate for anterior stromal disease; it only corrects endothelial dysfunction.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co07',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'A 35-year-old with progressive keratoconus (Kmax 58 D, pachymetry 440 um) requests corneal collagen cross-linking (CXL). Which contraindication applies?',
options:['A. Age over 30','B. Pachymetry less than 400 um at the thinnest point','C. Kmax greater than 55 D','D. Prior LASIK','E. Contact lens wear'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The minimum corneal thickness for standard (Dresden protocol) CXL is 400 um AFTER epithelial removal, as the UV-A light must not reach the endothelium (which would be damaged at depths beyond ~300 um of stroma). At 440 um total, after removing ~50 um of epithelium, the residual stroma would be ~390 um — below the 400 um threshold. Accelerated or modified protocols (hypotonic riboflavin to swell the cornea) may be used in thin corneas.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co08',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Herpes zoster ophthalmicus (HZO) involves the ophthalmic division of CN V. The Hutchinson sign (vesicles on the tip of the nose) predicts involvement of:',
options:['A. The lacrimal nerve','B. The frontal nerve','C. The nasociliary nerve','D. The supraorbital nerve','E. The infraorbital nerve'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'The nasociliary branch of V1 innervates both the tip of the nose (via the external nasal nerve) and the globe (via the long ciliary nerves). Hutchinson sign indicates nasociliary involvement, predicting a 76% risk of ocular involvement in HZO. The lacrimal nerve innervates the lacrimal gland and lateral upper lid. The frontal nerve innervates the forehead.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

// ── CORNEA (continued) ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'co09',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Bullous keratopathy after penetrating keratoplasty (PK) for Fuchs dystrophy most commonly results from:',
options:['A. Primary graft failure (donor endothelial dysfunction at time of surgery)','B. Immunologic rejection of donor endothelial cells','C. Elevated IOP post-transplant','D. Wound dehiscence from suture removal','E. Recurrence of Fuchs dystrophy in the graft'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Endothelial (immunologic) rejection is the most common cause of late PK failure. The rejection episode presents with KPs, AC inflammation, corneal edema, and Khodadoust line (endothelial rejection line). Treatment: intensive topical steroids ± systemic steroids urgently. Primary failure (pumping function never works) is the most common cause of early failure. Late rejection occurs months to years post-op.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co10',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Filamentary keratitis is MOST commonly associated with:',
options:['A. Bacterial keratitis','B. Viral keratitis','C. Severe dry eye syndrome','D. Corneal graft rejection','E. Acanthamoeba keratitis'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Filaments are strands of degenerated epithelial cells and mucus attached to the corneal surface, seen in severe aqueous-deficient dry eye. Other causes: superior limbic keratoconjunctivitis (SLK), prolonged patching, neuroparalytic keratitis, and recurrent erosion. Treatment: aggressive lubrication, bandage contact lens, mucolytic agents (NAC drops), punctal occlusion.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co11',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Thygeson superficial punctate keratitis (TSPK) is distinguished from viral SPK by:',
options:['A. Presence of anterior chamber inflammation in TSPK','B. Coarse, raised, epithelial opacities without subepithelial infiltrates, no follicles, excellent response to steroids','C. Positive viral PCR in TSPK','D. Profound photophobia with corneal vascularization in TSPK','E. TSPK is always bilateral while viral SPK is unilateral'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'TSPK features: bilateral coarse, round, raised granular epithelial opacities (NOT subepithelial), minimal to no conjunctival reaction, no follicles, no regional lymphadenopathy, no systemic illness, and excellent response to topical steroids. It is chronic with remissions/exacerbations. Viral (adenoviral) SPK has subepithelial infiltrates, follicles, papillae, pharyngitis (EKC), and pre-auricular lymphadenopathy.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co12',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient with anterior basement membrane dystrophy (ABMD/map-dot-fingerprint dystrophy) asks about LASIK. The MAIN concern is:',
options:['A. ABMD increases the risk of post-LASIK ectasia','B. ABMD increases the risk of post-LASIK recurrent epithelial erosions and flap complications','C. ABMD causes irregular astigmatism that cannot be corrected by LASIK','D. ABMD is a contraindication to any excimer laser surgery','E. ABMD causes excess corneal haze after LASIK'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'ABMD (epithelial basement membrane dystrophy) is the most common corneal dystrophy. In LASIK, poor epithelial adhesion (due to abnormal basement membrane) increases the risk of epithelial ingrowth, flap edge erosions, and recurrent erosion syndrome. PRK (surface ablation) is preferred over LASIK in ABMD patients, as there is no flap. ABMD is not a risk factor for ectasia (which relates to stromal thinning/keratoconus).',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co13',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The MOST common cause of infectious keratitis in developed countries is:',
options:['A. Fungal (Fusarium, Aspergillus)','B. Acanthamoeba','C. Herpes simplex virus','D. Bacterial (Pseudomonas, Staph)','E. Onchocerca volvulus'],
correct:'D',
explanation:'Bacterial keratitis is the most common infectious keratitis in developed countries, with Staphylococcus aureus and Pseudomonas aeruginosa being the leading organisms. In contact lens wearers, Pseudomonas predominates. Fungal keratitis is more common in tropical regions and after vegetable matter trauma. HSV keratitis is the most common infectious cause of corneal BLINDNESS in developed countries (due to cumulative scarring from recurrences).',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co14',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Salzmann nodular degeneration is characterized by:',
options:['A. Calcific deposits in Bowman layer causing band keratopathy','B. Elevated bluish-white stromal nodules arising from chronic epithelial inflammation, replacing Bowman layer','C. Deposition of amyloid in the anterior stroma','D. Lipid infiltration of the peripheral cornea','E. Iron deposits in the corneal epithelium'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Salzmann nodular degeneration: elevated, bluish-grey or white stromal nodules, usually in a mid-peripheral ring or following the limbus. It represents fibrous replacement of Bowman layer by fibrocellular tissue after chronic epithelial injury (trachoma, phlyctenulosis, longstanding contact lens wear). Treatment: superficial keratectomy or PTK. It is NOT a dystrophy (acquired, not genetic).',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co15',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Which topographic pattern is MOST concerning for keratoconus?',
options:['A. Symmetric bow-tie pattern with WTR astigmatism','B. Inferior steepening, skewed radial axes, and Kmax >47 D','C. Oblique astigmatism with a regular mire pattern','D. Generalized flattening with reduced anterior curvature','E. Asymmetric but stable topography over 3 years'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Keratoconus topographic features: inferior corneal steepening (infero-temporal ectasia), asymmetric bow-tie, skewed radial axis (SRAX, difference >20° between steep hemi-meridians), Kmax >47 D, and progressive steepening on serial maps. The ABCD and Amsler-Krumeich classifications grade severity. Any progressive change on serial topography/tomography is the key criterion for CXL candidacy.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co16',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Steven-Johnson syndrome (SJS) and toxic epidermal necrolysis (TEN) are distinguished by:',
options:['A. The causative drug — SJS is drug-induced, TEN is always idiopathic','B. Body surface area (BSA) involved: SJS <10%, overlap 10-30%, TEN >30%','C. Ocular involvement occurs only in TEN','D. SJS causes chronic ocular disease; TEN does not','E. TEN has worse immediate mortality but better long-term ocular outcomes'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'SJS and TEN are severe mucocutaneous reactions (typically drug-induced: sulfonamides, anticonvulsants, NSAIDs, allopurinol) involving epithelial sloughing. Classification by % BSA affected: SJS <10%, SJS/TEN overlap 10-30%, TEN >30%. Both can cause severe cicatrizing conjunctivitis → symblepharon, corneal pannus, keratinization, and blindness. TEN has ~30% mortality. Acute management: stop offending drug, ICU, IVIG, cyclosporine, amniotic membrane transplant.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co17',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The enzyme deficient in macular corneal dystrophy is:',
options:['A. Tyrosinase','B. Carbohydrate sulfotransferase 6 (CHST6) — keratan sulfate sulfotransferase','C. Galactosylceramidase','D. Alpha-galactosidase A','E. Hexosaminidase A'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Macular corneal dystrophy (MCD) is the ONLY autosomal RECESSIVE corneal stromal dystrophy (others are AD). It is caused by mutations in CHST6, encoding the enzyme N-acetylglucosamine-6-sulfotransferase, involved in keratan sulfate synthesis. Unsulfated keratan sulfate accumulates in keratocytes and endothelium, causing diffuse clouding with macular opacities extending to the limbus. Corneal thickness is reduced (unlike Granular and Lattice, which spare thickness).',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co18',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'The limbal stem cell niche is located:',
options:['A. In the superficial stromal layer of the peripheral cornea','B. In the basal epithelial layer of the limbus, in palisades of Vogt','C. In the Bowman layer at the corneal periphery','D. In the deep conjunctival crypts of the fornix','E. At the corneoscleral junction endothelium'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Limbal stem cells (LSCs) reside in the palisades of Vogt — the radially oriented epithelial ridges at the corneoscleral limbus (most prominent superiorly and inferiorly). These basal epithelial cells (p63+, ABCG2+) are the source of all corneal epithelial cells. Limbal stem cell deficiency (LSCD) from chemical burns, Stevens-Johnson syndrome, or aniridia causes conjunctivalization of the corneal surface. Treatment: CLET, SLET, or keratolimbal allograft.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co19',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A 50-year-old farmer presents with a corneal ulcer after being hit by a piece of grass. The ulcer has feathery edges with satellite lesions and a "dry-looking" infiltrate. The MOST likely organism is:',
options:['A. Pseudomonas aeruginosa','B. Staphylococcus aureus','C. Fusarium solani','D. Acanthamoeba','E. Herpes simplex virus'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Fungal keratitis (filamentous fungi: Fusarium, Aspergillus) classically follows vegetable matter or organic trauma. Features: feathery/irregular borders, satellite lesions, dry-looking or powdery infiltrate, immune ring, hypopyon, often minimal pain relative to size. Treatment: topical natamycin (Fusarium) or voriconazole (Aspergillus). Candida causes more regular/bacterial-looking keratitis in immunocompromised or post-surgery patients.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

{id:'co20',subject:'cornea',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The gold standard diagnostic test for Acanthamoeba keratitis is:',
options:['A. Corneal scraping with Giemsa stain','B. Corneal confocal microscopy showing cysts in situ','C. Culture on non-nutrient agar with E. coli overlay','D. PCR on corneal scraping','E. KOH preparation of corneal scraping'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Culture on non-nutrient agar seeded with E. coli (as a food source) is the gold standard for Acanthamoeba. The trophozoites eat bacteria and create "tracks" on the agar. Confocal microscopy is excellent for rapid diagnosis (visualizes cysts and trophozoites in vivo without scraping) and is becoming the preferred non-invasive diagnostic tool. PCR is highly sensitive but not universally available. KOH detects fungi, not Acanthamoeba.',
reference:'BCSC Section 8'},

// ── GLAUCOMA ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'gl01',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The normal range of central corneal thickness (CCT) is approximately:',
options:['A. 400-450 um','B. 500-560 um','C. 580-620 um','D. 450-480 um','E. 560-600 um'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Average CCT is approximately 540-545 um with a normal range of ~500-560 um. CCT significantly affects Goldmann applanation tonometry readings: thicker corneas give falsely HIGH readings; thinner corneas give falsely LOW readings. The Ocular Hypertension Treatment Study showed thin CCT is an independent risk factor for glaucoma conversion.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl02',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient has a cup-to-disc ratio of 0.8 with inferior notching and an arcuate scotoma on Humphrey visual field (24-2). IOP is 14 mmHg on two occasions. The MOST appropriate diagnosis is:',
options:['A. Physiologic cupping','B. Ocular hypertension','C. Normal-tension glaucoma','D. Angle-closure glaucoma suspect','E. Non-glaucomatous optic neuropathy'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Normal-tension glaucoma (NTG) is defined as glaucomatous optic neuropathy (structural loss: notching, thinning) with corresponding functional loss (VF defect) in the absence of elevated IOP (21 mmHg or less). IOP of 14 mmHg on two occasions meets this criterion. NTG is associated with vasospasm, systemic hypotension, Flammer syndrome, and obstructive sleep apnea.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl03',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Which glaucoma medication is CONTRAINDICATED in a patient with sickle cell disease?',
options:['A. Latanoprost','B. Timolol','C. Dorzolamide','D. Brimonidine','E. Pilocarpine'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors (dorzolamide, brinzolamide, acetazolamide) lower aqueous pH and bicarbonate, which can cause sickling of red blood cells in the anterior chamber and trabecular meshwork, potentially worsening IOP and causing vascular complications. Systemic CAIs are also contraindicated. Timolol is the safest option.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl04',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The Tube Versus Trabeculectomy (TVT) study showed that at 5 years:',
options:['A. Trabeculectomy had significantly lower IOP than tube shunt','B. Tube shunts had similar IOP control with fewer failures than trabeculectomy','C. Tube shunts had higher rates of hypotony maculopathy','D. Trabeculectomy had fewer late complications than tube shunts','E. Both procedures had similar failure rates and similar IOP'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The TVT study (5-year results): tube shunts (Baerveldt 350) and trabeculectomy with MMC had similar mean IOP (~14 mmHg). However, trabeculectomy had a higher cumulative failure rate (46.9%) vs tube shunts (29.8%). Trabeculectomy also had more early hypotony and vision-threatening complications. Tubes had more late complications (corneal, erosion).',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl05',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Pigment dispersion syndrome (PDS) is characterized by all of the following EXCEPT:',
options:['A. Krukenberg spindle','B. Sampaolesi line anterior to Schwalbe line','C. Radial iris transillumination defects','D. Dense trabecular pigmentation','E. Backward bowing of the iris'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Sampaolesi line (anterior to Schwalbe line) is seen in exfoliation syndrome/pseudoexfoliation glaucoma, not PDS. PDS features: Krukenberg spindle (pigment on corneal endothelium, vertical spindle-shaped), radial/spoke-wheel iris transillumination defects from posterior iris rubbing the lens zonules, dense trabecular meshwork pigmentation (360 degrees, most dense inferiorly), and posterior bowing (concave) of the iris due to reverse pupillary block.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl06',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A bleb-related endophthalmitis after trabeculectomy is MOST commonly caused by:',
options:['A. Staphylococcus aureus','B. Streptococcus species','C. Gram-negative organisms','D. Candida species','E. Haemophilus influenzae'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Late bleb-related endophthalmitis (blebitis/endophthalmitis) is most commonly caused by streptococcal species (Streptococcus pneumoniae, viridans streptococci), which account for ~20-30% of cases. Staphylococcus epidermidis and Haemophilus influenzae are also common. These are more virulent and have worse visual prognosis than typical post-cataract endophthalmitis (which is predominantly S. epidermidis).',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl07',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'In selective laser trabeculoplasty (SLT), the target chromophore is:',
options:['A. Water in trabecular cells','B. Melanin in pigmented trabecular meshwork cells','C. Hemoglobin in trabecular blood vessels','D. Collagen in the scleral spur','E. Lipofuscin in juxtacanalicular cells'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'SLT uses a Q-switched, frequency-doubled Nd:YAG laser (532 nm green) that selectively targets melanin-containing cells in the trabecular meshwork. The pulse duration (3 ns) is shorter than the thermal relaxation time of trabecular cells, so only pigmented cells are disrupted without collateral thermal damage to adjacent tissue (selective photothermolysis principle). This allows SLT to be safely repeated.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl08',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient with exfoliation glaucoma is scheduled for cataract surgery. The surgeon should anticipate:',
options:['A. Larger-than-average pupil dilation','B. Increased risk of zonular dialysis and vitreous loss','C. Lower risk of posterior capsule opacification','D. More accurate IOL power calculation','E. Reduced risk of postoperative IOP spike'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Pseudoexfoliation (PXF) material deposits on and weakens the zonules. Zonular fragility increases the risk of capsular-zonular dialysis, vitreous prolapse, and dropped nucleus. Other concerns: poor pupil dilation (PXF material on iris sphincter), risk of capsular contraction syndrome, and IOP spikes post-surgery. A capsular tension ring (CTR) should be available and used liberally if zonular weakness is noted.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

// ── GLAUCOMA (continued) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'gl09',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The AGIS (Advanced Glaucoma Intervention Study) showed that:',
options:['A. Aggressive IOP control to <18 mmHg prevents all VF progression','B. Eyes with IOP consistently near 0 mmHg had the least VF progression over 18 years','C. SLT was superior to ALT as a first-line procedure','D. Trabeculectomy was superior to tube shunts in all pressure ranges','E. Beta-blockers alone were sufficient for most patients'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'AGIS found that eyes with mean IOP consistently between 0-14 mmHg (or IOP ≤18 mmHg at all visits) showed no VF deterioration over 18 years, while eyes with higher IOP progressed. This established the importance of tight IOP control in advanced glaucoma and emphasized the concept of individualized target IOP. However, the study was observational after the initial randomization.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl10',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Primary acute angle-closure glaucoma presents with all of the following EXCEPT:',
options:['A. Severe eye pain and headache','B. Nausea and vomiting','C. Corneal edema with halos around lights','D. Gradual insidious onset over months','E. Mid-dilated, non-reactive pupil'],
correct:'D',
explanation:'Acute angle closure is a sudden, dramatic emergency — NOT insidious. Symptoms: sudden severe eye pain, headache, nausea/vomiting, blurred vision with colored halos (corneal edema), red eye. Signs: conjunctival injection, corneal epithelial edema, shallow AC, mid-dilated non-reactive pupil (from ischemia/iris sphincter damage), markedly elevated IOP (40-70+ mmHg). Chronic angle closure can be insidious.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl11',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Which MIGS (minimally invasive glaucoma surgery) procedure works by bypassing the trabecular meshwork to access Schlemm canal?',
options:['A. Canaloplasty','B. iStent (trabecular micro-bypass stent)','C. XEN gel stent','D. Preserflo MicroShunt','E. Ab externo trabeculectomy'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The iStent and iStent inject (Glaukos) are trabecular micro-bypass devices implanted ab interno through the trabecular meshwork directly into Schlemm\'s canal, bypassing the TM resistance (the main site of outflow obstruction in POAG). They enhance conventional outflow. XEN and Preserflo create subconjunctival drainage (like trabeculectomy but smaller). Canaloplasty dilates Schlemm\'s canal with a suture.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl12',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'In a Humphrey visual field 24-2 SITA Standard test, a "reliable" test requires:',
options:['A. Fixation loss <33%, false positive <15%, false negative <33%','B. Fixation loss <20%, false positive <20%, false negative <20%','C. No fixation losses','D. False positives <5% only','E. Any reliability indices are acceptable if the technician confirms attention'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Standard reliability criteria for Humphrey VF: fixation loss <33% (1 in 3 fixation checks), false positives <15%, and false negatives <33%. High false positives ("trigger happy") give artificially high sensitivity and should be interpreted cautiously. High false negatives may indicate advanced disease OR poor attention. Fixation losses >33% make the test unreliable for monitoring progression.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl13',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Cyclodialysis cleft causes hypotony by:',
options:['A. Increased aqueous production from ciliary body disruption','B. Separation of the ciliary body from the scleral spur, creating a direct passage to the suprachoroidal space','C. Damage to Schlemm canal with irreversible collapse','D. Posterior diversion of aqueous through a zonular defect','E. Disruption of the trabecular meshwork'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'A cyclodialysis cleft is a separation between the ciliary body and the scleral spur, created by trauma or iatrogenically (during angle surgery). It creates a direct communication between the anterior chamber and the suprachoroidal space, dramatically increasing uveoscleral outflow → profound hypotony. Management: cycloplegia (mydriatics close the cleft), laser or surgical repair. Sudden closure of a chronic cleft can cause acute IOP spike.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl14',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The OHTS (Ocular Hypertension Treatment Study) identified which factor as the STRONGEST predictor of conversion from OHT to POAG?',
options:['A. Age over 60','B. Cup-to-disc ratio >0.5','C. Central corneal thickness (CCT) <555 μm','D. African American race','E. Presence of disc hemorrhage'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'OHTS found CCT was the strongest predictor of POAG conversion: every 40 μm decrease in CCT approximately doubled the conversion risk. Other significant predictors: larger vertical C/D ratio, higher IOP, older age, and pattern standard deviation on VF. CCT also matters because thin corneas cause Goldmann tonometry to underestimate true IOP. African American race was associated with higher baseline C/D ratio and faster conversion.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl15',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Timolol eye drops (beta-blocker) lower IOP primarily by:',
options:['A. Increasing uveoscleral outflow','B. Increasing trabecular outflow facility','C. Decreasing aqueous humor production by the ciliary body','D. Constricting the episcleral veins','E. Decreasing choroidal blood volume'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Beta-blockers (timolol, betaxolol, levobunolol, carteolol) lower IOP by blocking beta-2 adrenergic receptors on the ciliary epithelium, reducing aqueous humor production by ~25-35%. They do not significantly affect outflow. Systemic effects: bradycardia, bronchospasm (contraindicated in asthma, significant COPD, heart block). Betaxolol is a selective beta-1 blocker with less bronchospasm risk.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl16',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient with primary open-angle glaucoma (POAG) on maximal medical therapy continues to progress. The IOP is 22 mmHg. The NEXT appropriate step is:',
options:['A. Add a 5th topical medication','B. Refer for glaucoma filtering surgery (trabeculectomy or tube shunt)','C. Repeat visual field testing in 6 months','D. Perform gonioscopy again','E. Check compliance with current medications'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'When a glaucoma patient is on maximal tolerated medical therapy (typically 3-4 medications targeting different mechanisms) and continues to progress, surgical intervention is indicated. "Maximal medical therapy" means the patient is on the maximum tolerated combination of medications. Adding a 5th medication is unlikely to provide significant additional benefit and adds side effects. Surgical options: trabeculectomy with MMC, tube shunt, or laser trabeculoplasty.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl17',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Neovascular glaucoma (NVG) most commonly results from which underlying condition?',
options:['A. Uveitis','B. Central retinal vein occlusion or proliferative diabetic retinopathy','C. Trauma','D. Iridocorneal endothelial (ICE) syndrome','E. Fuchs heterochromic iridocyclitis'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Neovascular glaucoma (NVG) results from anterior segment neovascularization (rubeosis iridis) secondary to posterior segment ischemia. Most common causes: central retinal vein occlusion (CRVO, especially ischemic — ~45% develop NVG within 3 months), proliferative diabetic retinopathy (PDR), and central retinal artery occlusion. Treatment: address the underlying ischemia (PRP, anti-VEGF), control IOP (tube shunt preferred as blebs fail with neovascularization).',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl18',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Which class of glaucoma medication has the GREATEST IOP-lowering effect as monotherapy?',
options:['A. Beta-blockers (~25% reduction)','B. Alpha-2 agonists (~20% reduction)','C. Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors (~20% reduction)','D. Prostaglandin analogues (~30-35% reduction)','E. Miotic agents (~20% reduction)'],
correct:'D',
explanation:'Prostaglandin analogues (latanoprost, bimatoprost, travoprost, tafluprost) are the most effective single agents for IOP reduction, lowering IOP by approximately 25-35% from baseline. They are now the first-line topical therapy for most POAG patients. They primarily work by increasing uveoscleral (unconventional) outflow. Once-daily dosing (evening preferred) and minimal systemic side effects are additional advantages.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl19',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Gonioscopy is ESSENTIAL in the evaluation of a new glaucoma patient because:',
options:['A. It measures the cup-to-disc ratio more accurately than fundus exam','B. It determines whether the angle is open or closed, identifying the mechanism of glaucoma','C. It measures IOP more accurately than tonometry','D. It identifies the site of aqueous production','E. It is required to diagnose optic nerve damage'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Gonioscopy directly visualizes the iridocorneal angle to determine if it is open or closed, which is critical for differentiating open-angle from angle-closure glaucoma — conditions requiring fundamentally different management. It also identifies angle recession (after trauma), neovascularization (NVG), pigment (PDS), PXF material, and inflammatory membranes. Treatment (especially laser iridotomy vs. filtering surgery) depends entirely on the mechanism.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

{id:'gl20',subject:'glaucoma',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A disc hemorrhage on the optic nerve rim is associated with:',
options:['A. Benign, transient finding unrelated to glaucoma','B. Recent episode of acute angle closure','C. Glaucoma progression and is a sign of ongoing optic nerve damage','D. Recent ocular hypertensive crisis','E. Optic disc drusen'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Disc (Drance) hemorrhages — flame/splinter hemorrhages at the margin of the optic disc — are strongly associated with glaucomatous progression, particularly in normal-tension glaucoma. They indicate small vessel vasospasm/infarction. They typically resolve over 2-3 months but recurrence is common. Their presence should prompt IOP re-evaluation and more frequent monitoring. Hemorrhages outside the disc margin are not Drance hemorrhages.',
reference:'BCSC Section 10'},

// ── RETINA & VITREOUS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'re01',subject:'retina',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'A 65-year-old presents with sudden onset of painless vision loss, described as a "curtain" coming across the vision. The MOST urgent evaluation is for:',
options:['A. Central retinal artery occlusion','B. Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment','C. Vitreous hemorrhage','D. Central serous chorioretinopathy','E. Age-related macular degeneration'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'A "curtain" or "shadow" coming across the visual field is the classic description of a rhegmatogenous retinal detachment (RRD) with the advancing edge of detached retina causing a corresponding visual field defect. This is a surgical emergency. CRAO causes sudden, painless, complete or near-complete vision loss (no curtain description). Vitreous hemorrhage causes floaters/red haze.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re02',subject:'retina',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Anti-VEGF therapy is the standard of care for which condition?',
options:['A. Non-proliferative diabetic retinopathy without macular edema','B. Neovascular (wet) age-related macular degeneration','C. Non-exudative (dry) AMD with drusen only','D. Epiretinal membrane','E. Vitreomacular traction syndrome'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Anti-VEGF agents (ranibizumab, bevacizumab, aflibercept, brolucizumab, faricimab) are the standard of care for neovascular (wet) AMD, significantly improving visual outcomes compared to natural history. They are also used for diabetic macular edema (DME), macular edema from CRVO/BRVO. Non-exudative AMD has no proven treatment (complements/AREDS2 for intermediate). ERM and VMT are treated surgically (vitrectomy).',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re03',subject:'retina',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'The HARBOR trial compared monthly vs. as-needed (PRN) ranibizumab for neovascular AMD. The main finding was:',
options:['A. PRN dosing was superior to monthly in visual acuity outcomes','B. Monthly and PRN dosing had equivalent visual outcomes; monthly required fewer injections','C. Monthly dosing showed superior visual outcomes; PRN was non-inferior only in the 2.0 mg arm','D. PRN dosing was associated with more geographic atrophy','E. Monthly dosing achieved better anatomic outcomes with similar visual acuity at 2 years'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'HARBOR compared ranibizumab 0.5 mg monthly vs PRN and 2.0 mg monthly vs PRN. Monthly dosing (both doses) achieved superior mean VA gains vs PRN at 24 months. The 2.0 mg PRN group was non-inferior to 0.5 mg monthly. This suggests monthly dosing is optimal but high-dose PRN may approximate it. This contrasts with CATT which showed bevacizumab PRN was not inferior to ranibizumab monthly.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re04',subject:'retina',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'In a patient with branch retinal artery occlusion (BRAO), the visual field defect is:',
options:['A. Central scotoma','B. Altitudinal defect respecting the horizontal meridian','C. Sectoral defect corresponding to the affected retinal territory','D. Bitemporal hemianopia','E. Homonymous hemianopia'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'BRAO causes infarction of the retinal territory supplied by the affected branch. This produces a sectoral (wedge-shaped) visual field defect corresponding to that retinal area. The superior temporal branch is most commonly affected (possibly due to embolus pathway), causing an inferior nasal sector defect. Altitudinal defects (respecting the horizontal meridian) are more typical of anterior ischemic optic neuropathy (AION).',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re05',subject:'retina',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Diabetic macular edema (DME) is defined as retinal thickening or hard exudates within:',
options:['A. 1 disc diameter of the fovea','B. 500 um of the fovea center','C. 1 disc diameter of the optic disc','D. 2 disc diameters of the fovea','E. The foveal avascular zone only'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Clinically significant macular edema (CSME) — the classic definition — includes retinal thickening within 500 um of the fovea center, hard exudates within 500 um of the fovea with adjacent thickening, or retinal thickening of 1 disc area or more within 1 disc diameter of the fovea. For practical purposes, DME/CSME involves changes within 1 disc diameter of the fovea.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re06',subject:'retina',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'A patient with proliferative diabetic retinopathy develops sudden visual loss with an ultrasound showing a tractional retinal detachment involving the macula. The BEST surgical approach is:',
options:['A. Scleral buckle only','B. Panretinal photocoagulation to regress neovascularization before surgery','C. Pars plana vitrectomy with membrane peeling','D. Anti-VEGF injection alone','E. Observe for 6 weeks for spontaneous resolution'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Tractional retinal detachment (TRD) involving the macula is an indication for pars plana vitrectomy (PPV) with careful membrane dissection (delamination/segmentation) to relieve traction. Anti-VEGF 3-7 days pre-op can reduce bleeding and facilitate membrane peeling (adjunctive, not definitive). Scleral buckle is not appropriate for TRD (no break to close). PRP may worsen TRD by causing fibrovascular contraction.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re07',subject:'retina',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Vogt-Koyanagi-Harada (VKH) disease in the acute uveitic phase classically shows on FA/ICGA:',
options:['A. Multifocal chorioretinitis with "punched-out" lesions','B. Disc hyperfluorescence and multifocal pinpoint subretinal leakage in a "starry sky" pattern','C. Frosted branch angiitis','D. Choroidal ischemia with watershed zone infarction','E. Macular star with disc edema'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Acute VKH shows bilateral exudative retinal detachments. FA demonstrates disc leakage, multifocal pinpoint RPE leaks at the level of choroidal stroma giving a "starry sky" appearance, and pooling in subretinal space. ICGA shows hypofluorescent dark dots (choroidal inflammation). Delayed VKH shows "sunset glow" fundus (depigmentation), Dalen-Fuchs nodules, perilimbal vitiligo (Sugiura sign).',
reference:'BCSC Section 9/12'},

{id:'re08',subject:'retina',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Which of the following is MOST characteristic of retinitis pigmentosa (RP)?',
options:['A. Central scotoma and color vision loss early','B. Night blindness and peripheral visual field loss with bone spicule pigmentation','C. Rapid progression to blindness within 5 years','D. Autosomal dominant inheritance only','E. Normal electroretinogram (ERG) until late stages'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'RP classically presents with nyctalopia (night blindness) from early rod photoreceptor loss, progressing to peripheral visual field constriction ("tunnel vision") and bone spicule pigment migration. Central vision is relatively preserved until late. ERG shows reduced rod and cone responses early. Inheritance: autosomal dominant (most common, ~30-40%), autosomal recessive (~50-60%), X-linked (most severe).',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

// ── RETINA (continued) ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'re09',subject:'retina',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Central serous chorioretinopathy (CSCR) is most commonly associated with:',
options:['A. Corticosteroid use and type A personality','B. Elevated VEGF levels in the choroid','C. Autoimmune disease and systemic inflammation','D. Diabetic microangiopathy','E. Age-related Bruch membrane changes'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'CSCR involves focal RPE detachment and leakage of fluid from the choroidal vasculature into the subretinal space. Risk factors: exogenous corticosteroids (any route — systemic, topical, inhaled), endogenous hypercortisolemia (Cushing\'s), type A personality, stress, obstructive sleep apnea, and male sex. It is a pachychoroid spectrum disease. FA shows a classic "smokestack" or "inkblot" pattern. Most resolve spontaneously in 3-4 months.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re10',subject:'retina',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'The CATT (Comparison of AMD Treatments Trial) compared ranibizumab vs. bevacizumab for neovascular AMD. The main conclusion was:',
options:['A. Ranibizumab was superior in VA outcomes at 2 years','B. Bevacizumab had significantly more systemic adverse events','C. Bevacizumab was non-inferior to ranibizumab in VA outcomes and was cost-effective','D. Monthly dosing was inferior to PRN for both drugs','E. Neither drug reduced geographic atrophy progression'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'CATT (2011, 2012): bevacizumab (Avastin, off-label) was non-inferior to ranibizumab (Lucentis) for visual acuity outcomes at 1 and 2 years. Monthly dosing was superior to PRN for anatomic outcomes but equivalent for VA. Bevacizumab had slightly higher (but not statistically significant) rates of serious systemic adverse events (hospitalizations) in some analyses. The cost difference is massive (~$50 vs $2000/injection), making bevacizumab extremely cost-effective.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re11',subject:'retina',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient with a macular hole is referred for vitrectomy. Which OCT finding indicates a FULL-THICKNESS macular hole requiring surgery?',
options:['A. Disruption of the IS/OS (ellipsoid zone) only','B. Vitreomacular traction without foveal contour disruption','C. Full-thickness foveal defect with loss of all retinal layers on OCT','D. Intraretinal cysts in the foveal area only','E. Subretinal fluid at the fovea without a break'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'A full-thickness macular hole (FTMH) on OCT shows a complete break through all retinal layers — from the ILM to the outer segments/RPE — at the fovea. The International VMT Study Group classification: stage 1 (lamellar), stage 2-4 full-thickness (by size: <250 μm, 250-400 μm, >400 μm). FTMH treatment: PPV with ILM peeling and gas tamponade. 90%+ anatomic closure. Vision usually improves 2-3 lines.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re12',subject:'retina',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Photocoagulation (laser) is the treatment of choice for:',
options:['A. Neovascular AMD with subfoveal CNV','B. Proliferative diabetic retinopathy (panretinal photocoagulation)','C. Diabetic macular edema with center involvement','D. Non-proliferative DR without macular edema','E. Central retinal artery occlusion'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Panretinal photocoagulation (PRP) is the standard treatment for high-risk proliferative diabetic retinopathy (PDR) — neovascularization of the disc (NVD) or elsewhere (NVE) with high-risk characteristics. PRP destroys ischemic peripheral retina, reducing VEGF production and causing regression of new vessels. Anti-VEGF (ranibizumab, Protocol S DRCR.net) has emerged as an alternative with better central vision outcomes but requires more frequent visits.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re13',subject:'retina',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Which inherited retinal dystrophy is X-linked and characterized by a schisis of the inner retina at the fovea with a classic "spoke wheel" or "bicycle wheel" pattern on OCT?',
options:['A. Best vitelliform macular dystrophy','B. Stargardt disease (ABCA4)','C. X-linked juvenile retinoschisis (XLRS)','D. Enhanced S-cone syndrome','E. Goldmann-Favre syndrome'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'X-linked juvenile retinoschisis (XLRS) is caused by mutations in RS1 (retinoschisin gene), which encodes a secreted protein important for photoreceptor-bipolar cell adhesion. It affects males in the first decade with reduced VA and foveal schisis on OCT (stellate/spoke-wheel pattern) and extrafoveal schisis in 50%. ERG shows reduced b-wave (inner retinal dysfunction) with preserved a-wave. Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors (dorzolamide, acetazolamide) can reduce the schisis.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re14',subject:'retina',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The primary treatment for a symptomatic posterior vitreous detachment (PVD) complicated by a horseshoe (flap) tear WITHOUT detachment is:',
options:['A. Immediate pars plana vitrectomy','B. Observation only — horseshoe tears rarely detach','C. Barrier laser photocoagulation around the tear','D. Pneumatic retinopexy','E. Scleral buckle'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'A symptomatic (new) horseshoe tear (retinal flap tear with vitreous traction) has a significant risk (~30-50%) of progressing to retinal detachment if untreated. Standard treatment: barrier laser photocoagulation (retinopexy) 2-3 rows around the tear to create a chorioretinal adhesion and seal the break. Cryotherapy is an alternative. Asymptomatic or operculated (free-floating) holes may not require treatment.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re15',subject:'retina',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The MOST common primary intraocular malignancy in adults is:',
options:['A. Retinoblastoma','B. Choroidal osteoma','C. Uveal melanoma','D. Choroidal hemangioma','E. Vitreoretinal lymphoma'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Uveal melanoma is the most common primary intraocular malignancy in adults, arising from melanocytes of the iris, ciliary body, or choroid. The choroid is the most common site. Risk factors: fair skin, light iris, dysplastic nevus syndrome, and ocular/oculodermal melanocytosis. COMS trial showed brachytherapy (plaque) equivalent to enucleation for medium tumors. Metastasis to the liver is most common and is the leading cause of death.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re16',subject:'retina',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A 45-year-old woman is found to have a pigmented choroidal lesion of 3 disc diameters, elevation 2.5 mm. Which factor is MOST associated with malignant transformation?',
options:['A. Orange pigment (lipofuscin) overlying the lesion','B. Sharp, distinct borders','C. Absence of subretinal fluid','D. Stable size over 2 years','E. Presence of drusen overlying the lesion'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'The Collaborative Ocular Melanoma Study (COMS) identified "MOLES" risk factors for malignant transformation of choroidal nevi: Mushroom shape, Orange pigment, Large diameter (>5 mm), Elevation (>2 mm), Subretinal fluid. Orange pigment (lipofuscin deposition from disrupted RPE) is the strongest individual predictor. Absence of drusen also increases suspicion (drusen = chronic, stable nevi).',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re17',subject:'retina',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Faricimab (Vabysmo) differs from other anti-VEGF agents in that it:',
options:['A. Is a VEGF-A trap with higher binding affinity than aflibercept','B. Is a bispecific antibody targeting both VEGF-A and angiopoietin-2 (Ang-2)','C. Is an oral VEGF receptor tyrosine kinase inhibitor','D. Acts on VEGF-C and VEGF-D exclusively','E. Is a pegylated anti-VEGF fragment with longer duration'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Faricimab (Vabysmo, Roche/Genentech) is the first bispecific ophthalmic antibody — it simultaneously targets VEGF-A (reducing vascular permeability and neovascularization) and Ang-2 (promoting vascular stability through the Tie2 pathway). Ang-2 destabilizes blood vessels and is upregulated in AMD and DME. Phase III TENAYA/LUCERNE (AMD) and YOSEMITE/RHINE (DME) showed extended dosing (up to every 16 weeks) with comparable efficacy to every-8-week aflibercept.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re18',subject:'retina',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Acute retinal necrosis (ARN) is caused by which organisms?',
options:['A. Toxoplasma gondii only','B. CMV in immunocompetent patients','C. VZV, HSV-1, or HSV-2 (herpesviruses)','D. EBV and CMV','E. Syphilis'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'ARN (Acute Retinal Necrosis) syndrome is caused by herpesviruses — primarily VZV (varicella-zoster virus) and HSV-1/HSV-2. It occurs in immunocompetent patients. Features: peripheral necrotizing retinitis, occlusive arteritis, severe vitritis, rapid circumferential spread, and high risk of RD (50-75% due to multiple peripheral breaks). Treatment: IV acyclovir or oral valacyclovir for 2-3 weeks, then oral antiviral prophylaxis. CMV retinitis occurs almost exclusively in immunocompromised patients.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re19',subject:'retina',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'In the DRCR.net Protocol T trial, which anti-VEGF agent showed the best visual acuity outcomes in diabetic macular edema (DME)?',
options:['A. Bevacizumab (Avastin)','B. Ranibizumab (Lucentis)','C. Aflibercept (Eylea) — especially in eyes with initial VA ≤20/50','D. All three were equivalent in all VA subgroups','E. Pegaptanib (Macugen)'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Protocol T (2015) compared bevacizumab, ranibizumab, and aflibercept for DME. At 1 year: when initial VA was 20/32-20/40 (good baseline), all three were equivalent. When initial VA was ≤20/50 (worse baseline), aflibercept showed significantly greater VA improvement than bevacizumab, with intermediate results for ranibizumab. At 2 years, differences were less pronounced as bevacizumab and ranibizumab could receive aflibercept if needed.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

{id:'re20',subject:'retina',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'In pneumatic retinopexy for rhegmatogenous RD, which factor is MOST associated with failure?',
options:['A. Single break in the superior 8 clock hours','B. Break size greater than 1 clock hour','C. Multiple breaks in different quadrants','D. Phakic eye','E. Recent (less than 1 week) onset of detachment'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Pneumatic retinopexy success requires the gas bubble to cover the break(s). Multiple breaks in different quadrants cannot all be tamponaded simultaneously by a single gas bubble. Other relative contraindications: inferior breaks (bubble cannot reach), breaks outside the superior 8 clock hours, significant PVR, failed previous retinal surgery. Single superior break: ideal candidate with ~80% primary success. C3F8 (14% concentration) lasts 8-10 weeks; SF6 (20%) lasts 2-3 weeks.',
reference:'BCSC Section 12'},

// ── OCULOPLASTICS & ORBIT ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'pl01',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A 55-year-old presents with unilateral proptosis, resistance to retropulsion, and an afferent pupillary defect. CT shows an infiltrative orbital mass with bone erosion. The MOST likely diagnosis is:',
options:['A. Cavernous hemangioma','B. Thyroid eye disease','C. Orbital lymphoma','D. Metastatic carcinoma','E. Idiopathic orbital inflammatory syndrome (orbital pseudotumor)'],
correct:'D',
explanation:'Bone erosion on CT is a red flag for malignancy. Metastatic carcinoma (breast in women, prostate in men most commonly) can cause osteolytic or osteoblastic bone changes. Lymphoma typically does NOT erode bone. Cavernous hemangioma is well-circumscribed without bone changes. Thyroid eye disease shows muscle enlargement but no bone erosion. APD indicates optic nerve compression.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl02',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The most common benign orbital tumor in adults is:',
options:['A. Rhabdomyosarcoma','B. Lymphoma','C. Cavernous venous malformation (cavernous hemangioma)','D. Dermoid cyst','E. Neurofibroma'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Cavernous venous malformation (historically called cavernous hemangioma) is the most common benign orbital tumor in adults. It presents as slow progressive painless proptosis in middle-aged women. CT shows a well-circumscribed, homogeneous intraconal mass with enhancement. It does NOT require treatment unless causing compressive optic neuropathy or significant cosmetic deformity. Rhabdomyosarcoma is the most common primary orbital malignancy in children.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl03',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'In thyroid eye disease (TED), the extraocular muscle affected MOST commonly (and earliest) is the:',
options:['A. Superior rectus','B. Lateral rectus','C. Superior oblique','D. Inferior rectus','E. Medial rectus'],
correct:'D',
explanation:'The inferior rectus is the most commonly affected muscle in TED, causing hypotropia and restriction of upgaze (due to fibrosis). Mnemonic: "I\'M SLow" — Inferior, Medial, Superior, Lateral (in descending order of frequency). The inferior rectus restriction can also cause an abnormal head position and diplopia worse in upgaze.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl04',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'The clinical activity score (CAS) in thyroid eye disease is used to:',
options:['A. Determine the severity of proptosis','B. Predict visual loss risk from compressive optic neuropathy','C. Assess inflammatory activity to guide immunosuppressive treatment timing','D. Measure diplopia severity for surgical planning','E. Determine risk of corneal exposure'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'The Clinical Activity Score (CAS) uses 7 parameters (pain at rest, pain on eye movement, redness of eyelids, redness of conjunctiva, chemosis, swollen caruncle/plica, lid edema) to score inflammatory activity 0-7. A CAS of 3 or more out of 7 suggests active disease that is likely to respond to immunosuppression (IV methylprednisolone, teprotumumab). CAS guides WHEN to treat with immunosuppression, not the severity of structural damage.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl05',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A biopsy of an eyelid lesion shows nests of basaloid cells with peripheral palisading and retraction artifact. The diagnosis is:',
options:['A. Squamous cell carcinoma','B. Sebaceous gland carcinoma','C. Basal cell carcinoma','D. Merkel cell carcinoma','E. Lymphoma'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is the most common eyelid malignancy (>90%). Histology shows nests or cords of basaloid cells with peripheral palisading (nuclei aligned at the periphery of nests) and retraction artifact (stromal retraction around nests). It most commonly occurs on the lower eyelid. Treatment: surgical excision with Mohs micrographic surgery for eyelid lesions. BCC metastasizes very rarely.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

// ── OCULOPLASTICS (continued) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'pl06',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Ptosis repair surgery in a patient with poor levator function (<4 mm) should utilize which technique?',
options:['A. Levator aponeurosis advancement','B. Müllerectomy (Putterman procedure)','C. Frontalis sling (suspension)','D. Whitnall sling procedure','E. Tarsectomy'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'The choice of ptosis repair depends on levator function: Good function (>8 mm) → levator aponeurosis advancement; Moderate function (4-7 mm) → levator resection; Poor function (<4 mm) → frontalis sling (using silicone rod, fascia lata, or Gore-Tex). Poor levator function indicates the levator is severely fibrotic/absent, so surgery must recruit the frontalis muscle to elevate the lid. Frontalis sling carries risk of lagophthalmos and exposure.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl07',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The MOST common malignant eyelid tumor is:',
options:['A. Squamous cell carcinoma','B. Melanoma','C. Basal cell carcinoma','D. Sebaceous gland carcinoma','E. Merkel cell carcinoma'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) accounts for over 90% of eyelid malignancies. It most commonly occurs on the LOWER eyelid medially (70%), followed by medial canthus, upper eyelid, and lateral canthus. Risk: UV exposure, fair skin, age. Treatment: surgical excision (Mohs surgery preferred for lid margin or medial canthal involvement). BCC virtually never metastasizes but can cause local bone invasion. Sebaceous gland carcinoma is rare but highly malignant.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl08',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Orbital apex syndrome includes:',
options:['A. CN II, III, IV, V1, and VI deficits (visual loss + ophthalmoplegia + V1 sensory loss)','B. Only cranial nerve III, IV, and VI (ophthalmoplegia without visual loss)','C. Cavernous sinus involvement with bilateral findings','D. CN VII and VIII involvement','E. CN III and VI palsy with ipsilateral Horner syndrome'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Orbital apex syndrome involves structures passing through both the superior orbital fissure (CN III, IV, V1, VI, sympathetics) AND the optic canal (CN II). Thus: ophthalmoplegia (III, IV, VI), ptosis (III and sympathetics), V1 sensory loss, Horner, and — critically — optic neuropathy/visual loss (CN II). Causes: metastasis, mucormycosis, sarcoidosis, cavernous sinus thrombosis. Cavernous sinus syndrome spares the optic nerve (it is outside the cavernous sinus).',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl09',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The MOST common cause of unilateral proptosis in adults is:',
options:['A. Cavernous hemangioma','B. Thyroid eye disease (TED)','C. Orbital lymphoma','D. Orbital cellulitis','E. Lacrimal gland tumor'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Thyroid eye disease (Graves orbitopathy) is the most common cause of both unilateral AND bilateral proptosis in adults. It causes extraocular muscle enlargement (sparing the tendons), orbital fat expansion, and increased orbital pressure. Even when bilateral, it is often asymmetric and may initially appear unilateral. TED is diagnosed clinically + orbital imaging (CT shows fusiform muscle enlargement with tendon sparing) + thyroid function tests.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl10',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'In orbital blowout fracture of the orbital floor, which extraocular muscle is MOST commonly entrapped?',
options:['A. Medial rectus','B. Inferior rectus and/or inferior oblique','C. Superior rectus','D. Lateral rectus','E. Superior oblique'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Orbital floor fractures (blowout) occur from sudden pressure increase (blunt trauma). The inferior rectus and inferior oblique muscles (or their fascial connections) can be entrapped in the fractured floor through the maxillary sinus. Clinical signs: restricted upgaze (diplopia in upgaze), enophthalmos, infraorbital nerve hypesthesia (cheek/upper lip numbness). The "white-eyed blowout" in children is a pediatric emergency — significant entrapment with oculocardiac reflex (nausea/bradycardia) despite minimal external trauma.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl11',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Sebaceous gland carcinoma of the eyelid is associated with all of the following EXCEPT:',
options:['A. Masquerade syndrome (mimicking chalazion, blepharitis, or conjunctivitis)','B. Pagetoid spread through the epithelium','C. Meibomian gland or Zeis gland origin','D. Association with Muir-Torre syndrome','E. Metastasis is virtually unknown (like BCC)'],
correct:'E',
explanation:'Sebaceous gland carcinoma is a HIGH-GRADE malignancy with significant metastatic potential (regional lymph nodes, then systemic). Mortality can be 15-30% depending on staging. It masquerades as chalazion or chronic blepharoconjunctivitis (masquerade syndrome). Pagetoid spread along the conjunctival and corneal epithelium is characteristic — requires map biopsies. Associated with Muir-Torre syndrome (Lynch syndrome variant: sebaceous neoplasms + internal malignancies).',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl12',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A 6-year-old with unilateral ptosis and poor levator function should be treated urgently if:',
options:['A. The ptosis is cosmetically noticeable to parents','B. Ptosis occludes the visual axis, risking deprivational amblyopia','C. The child shows an abnormal head tilt','D. There is associated astigmatism greater than 1 D','E. The ptosis is worse in the morning'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'In children, any ptosis that occludes the visual axis can cause severe deprivational amblyopia — even brief periods of occlusion in a young child impair visual cortex development. This is a surgical urgency. Even partial ptosis causing astigmatism or chin-up head posture may need earlier intervention. After surgery, amblyopia therapy (patching) of the fellow eye is often needed. Cosmesis alone is not an urgent indication.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl13',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Mucormycosis (Zygomycosis) affecting the orbit is most commonly seen in:',
options:['A. Healthy young adults','B. Poorly controlled diabetics with ketoacidosis and immunocompromised patients','C. Children with viral upper respiratory infections','D. Patients on systemic antibiotics','E. Elderly patients with well-controlled hypertension'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Rhinoorbital-cerebral mucormycosis is a rapidly fatal fungal infection caused by Mucor/Rhizopus species. Classic setting: uncontrolled diabetes with ketoacidosis, hematologic malignancies, organ transplant/immunosuppression, or deferoxamine use. The fungi require a high-iron, low-pH environment to grow (hence ketoacidosis). Presentation: black eschar on palate/turbinates, orbital cellulitis, proptosis, ophthalmoplegia, cavernous sinus thrombosis, carotid artery invasion. Treatment: surgical debridement + amphotericin B.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl14',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The MOST common type of lacrimal gland tumor that is benign is:',
options:['A. Adenoid cystic carcinoma','B. Pleomorphic adenoma (benign mixed tumor)','C. Mucoepidermoid carcinoma','D. Non-Hodgkin lymphoma','E. Dacryoadenitis (inflammatory)'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Lacrimal gland masses: ~50% epithelial, ~50% non-epithelial (lymphoid/inflammatory). Of epithelial tumors, ~50% are pleomorphic adenoma (benign mixed tumor) and ~50% are malignant (adenoid cystic carcinoma most common malignant, ~50% of malignant). Pleomorphic adenoma: slow-growing, painless, supero-temporal proptosis, CT shows smooth globular mass without bone erosion. Treatment: complete excision WITHOUT incising the capsule (seeding causes recurrence). Do NOT perform incisional biopsy.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

{id:'pl15',subject:'oculoplastics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Involutional ectropion of the lower eyelid is caused by:',
options:['A. Scarring and shortening of the anterior lamella','B. CN VII palsy causing orbicularis weakness','C. Horizontal lid laxity with inferior displacement of the tarsus','D. Posterior lamella scarring from chronic conjunctivitis','E. Proptosis causing anterior displacement of the eyelid'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Involutional (senile) ectropion results from age-related horizontal eyelid laxity — medial and lateral canthal tendon attenuation causes the lower lid to sag outward. Treatment: horizontal lid-shortening procedure (lateral tarsal strip being most common). Cicatricial ectropion (from anterior lamella scarring — burn, trauma, BCC excision) is treated with Z-plasty or skin grafting. Paralytic ectropion (CN VII palsy) needs lubricants, weights, or temporary/permanent tarsorrhaphy.',
reference:'BCSC Section 7'},

// ── PEDIATRIC OPHTHALMOLOGY & STRABISMUS ──────────────────────────────────────
{id:'pe01',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'A 3-year-old presents with a constant right esotropia of 30 prism diopters. Cycloplegic refraction shows +5.00 D OU. The FIRST treatment should be:',
options:['A. Immediate surgical correction of the esotropia','B. Full cycloplegic spectacle correction','C. Patching of the left eye for amblyopia','D. Botulinum toxin injection into the right medial rectus','E. Prism therapy'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'This is accommodative esotropia. The high hyperopia (+5.00 D) drives excess accommodative convergence, causing the esotropia. Treatment: FULL cycloplegic spectacle correction first. Once proper glasses are worn, the esotropia may fully or partially resolve. If residual deviation remains after 3-6 months of glasses wear, surgery addresses the non-accommodative component. Amblyopia treatment is concurrent if present.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe02',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The AC/A ratio is elevated in which type of esotropia?',
options:['A. Congenital (infantile) esotropia','B. Sensory esotropia','C. Basic esotropia','D. Convergence excess esotropia','E. Divergence insufficiency'],
correct:'D',
explanation:'Convergence excess esotropia has a high AC/A ratio — the esotropia is significantly larger at near than at distance. Treatment: bifocals (executive style, +3.00 D add) to reduce the accommodative convergence at near. Alternatively, miotics (echothiophate). Infantile esotropia has a normal or variable AC/A. The AC/A ratio = (esotropia at near - esotropia at far in PD) / accommodation in diopters.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe03',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'A 6-month-old is found to have leukocoria in the right eye. B-scan ultrasound shows calcification. The MOST likely diagnosis is:',
options:['A. Cataract','B. Retinopathy of prematurity','C. Retinoblastoma','D. Persistent fetal vasculature (PFV)','E. Coats disease'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Leukocoria with calcification (high-reflectivity foci on B-scan / calcification on CT) in a child under 3 is retinoblastoma until proven otherwise. Retinoblastoma is the most common primary intraocular malignancy in children. Calcification within the mass on ultrasound or CT is pathognomonic. PFV (persistent fetal vasculature) also causes leukocoria but is typically unilateral, has a stalk, and microphthalmia without calcification.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe04',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Brown syndrome is characterized by:',
options:['A. Inability to adduct in all fields of gaze','B. Limitation of elevation in adduction due to a tight superior oblique tendon sheath','C. Esotropia that is larger in upgaze than downgaze','D. Alternating hypertropia in primary position','E. Downward and inward deviation of the affected eye'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Brown syndrome is caused by a tight or thickened superior oblique tendon-trochlear complex, restricting the inferior oblique\'s elevation in adduction (which it opposes). Key features: restricted elevation in adduction, normal or near-normal elevation in abduction, no superior oblique overaction, widening of the palpebral fissure on attempted adduction-elevation, and a "click" sometimes palpable at the trochlea.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe05',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The critical period for amblyopia treatment (patching) is:',
options:['A. Birth to 6 months','B. Birth to 3 years','C. Up to approximately 7-9 years','D. Up to 18 years','E. Adults can develop amblyopia as readily as children'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'The visual cortex has a critical period of plasticity during which visual deprivation can cause amblyopia and during which patching/treatment can reverse it. This period extends approximately to age 7-9 years (end of the sensitive period). After this, amblyopia treatment becomes less effective. However, some residual plasticity persists into early teenage years, and patching can still help up to about age 12-17 with decreasing efficacy.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

// ── PEDIATRICS (continued) ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'pe06',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Retinopathy of prematurity (ROP) zone I disease requires treatment at:',
options:['A. Any stage in zone I','B. Stage 1 or 2 in zone I without plus disease','C. Stage 3 or plus disease in zone I (or aggressive posterior ROP)','D. Stage 3 in any zone without plus disease','E. Plus disease only in zone III'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Treatment criteria (ETROP study): "Type 1 ROP" requires treatment: Zone I — any stage with plus disease, or Stage 3 without plus; Zone II — Stage 2 or 3 WITH plus disease. Aggressive posterior ROP (AP-ROP, formerly "Rush disease") in zone I/II requires immediate treatment. Treatment: laser photocoagulation or bevacizumab (anti-VEGF). Bevacizumab is preferred for Zone I (laser cannot adequately cover) but requires long follow-up (late recurrence possible).',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe07',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'A 2-year-old has a white reflex. Exam under anesthesia shows a unilateral mass in the eye. CT shows calcification and the mass is T2-hypointense on MRI. The child has a family history of similar condition. Which gene mutation is most likely?',
options:['A. TP53 (Li-Fraumeni syndrome)','B. BRCA1','C. RB1 (retinoblastoma gene) — tumor suppressor','D. PTEN','E. APC'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Retinoblastoma is caused by biallelic inactivation of RB1 (chromosome 13q14) — a classic tumor suppressor gene (two-hit hypothesis). Hereditary (germline) Rb: ~40% of cases, bilateral or multifocal, earlier onset, autosomal dominant with 90% penetrance, risk of secondary malignancies (osteosarcoma, etc.). Sporadic (somatic): ~60%, unilateral, single tumor. Children with hereditary Rb should have genetic counseling and long-term cancer surveillance.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe08',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient has a 30 PD exotropia at distance and 12 PD at near. This pattern (larger at distance) is:',
options:['A. Convergence excess exotropia','B. Basic exotropia','C. Divergence excess exotropia','D. Convergence insufficiency','E. Sensory exotropia'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Divergence excess exotropia: XT significantly larger at distance than at near (ratio >2:1 or difference >10 PD). The pathophysiology involves excessive divergence at distance. Treatment: surgical correction of the angle (typically recession of both lateral recti). Distinguish from simulated divergence excess — if high AC/A ratio, the near deviation increases when tested with +3 D lenses. Convergence excess XT = near > distance.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe09',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The most common cause of acquired esotropia in a child aged 18 months to 4 years is:',
options:['A. CN VI palsy','B. Congenital (infantile) esotropia','C. Accommodative esotropia from uncorrected hyperopia','D. Sensory esotropia from poor vision','E. Thyroid eye disease'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Accommodative esotropia is the most common type of esotropia presenting in the toddler-preschool age group. It is caused by uncorrected hyperopia: the extra accommodation needed to clear the blurred image drives accommodative convergence, exceeding the fusional divergence capacity. Treatment: full cycloplegic spectacle correction. Infantile esotropia presents earlier (<6 months). CN VI palsy is acute and associated with a head turn.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe10',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Duane retraction syndrome type I is characterized by:',
options:['A. Limited abduction, globe retraction on attempted adduction, narrowing of palpebral fissure','B. Limited adduction only','C. Limited both abduction and adduction','D. Exotropia in primary position with limited abduction','E. Superior oblique overaction with V-pattern'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Duane retraction syndrome (DRS) Type I: Limited/absent abduction (most common, 70-80%), normal or limited adduction, globe retraction and palpebral fissure narrowing on adduction (from co-contraction of lateral and medial recti innervated by CN III branch). Caused by absent CN VI nucleus with CN III fibers co-innervating the lateral rectus. Type II: limited adduction. Type III: limited both. Treatment: surgery only for significant head turn or exotropia in primary position.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe11',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Which statement about intermittent exotropia (IXT) management is MOST accurate?',
options:['A. Surgery is always indicated when the deviation exceeds 20 PD','B. The PEDIG IXT study showed observation equivalent to surgery for control score of 2 or less','C. Patching of the deviating eye has been shown to be superior to surgery','D. PEDIG IXT3 trial showed bilateral lateral rectus recession equivalent to unilateral recess-resect','E. Anti-VEGF reduces the angle of deviation in IXT'],
correct:'D',
explanation:'The PEDIG IXT3 trial (2019) compared bilateral lateral rectus recession (BLR) vs. unilateral lateral rectus recession + medial rectus resection (R&R) for IXT. Both procedures showed equivalent motor and sensory outcomes at 3 years. However, BLR had slightly better results for larger angle deviations. The IXTSS (IXT Surgical Timing Study) found no benefit to early vs. late surgery for most IXT. Patching improves control score but evidence for long-term benefit is mixed.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe12',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Anisometropic amblyopia typically results from:',
options:['A. A difference in refractive error between the two eyes causing chronic defocus in one eye','B. Constant strabismus from birth','C. Cataract present at birth','D. Occlusion of one eye with a patch in an adult','E. Nystagmus blocking syndrome'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Anisometropic amblyopia occurs when there is a significant difference in refractive error (anisometropia) between the two eyes. The eye with worse refractive error receives a chronically blurred image, leading to suppression and failure of cortical development. Significant anisometropia: ≥1.50 D spherical equivalent difference, ≥1.00 D anisomyopia, or ≥1.50 D astigmatic difference. Treatment: correct the refractive error (glasses/contact lens) first, then occlusion therapy of the better eye.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe13',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The 4 prism diopter base-out test (4Δ BO test) detects:',
options:['A. Amblyopia in the tested eye','B. Microtropia or very small-angle strabismus with central suppression','C. Convergence insufficiency','D. Latent hyperopia','E. Superior oblique palsy'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The 4Δ BO test detects microtropia (small-angle strabismus <8 PD with central suppression). When 4 PD BO is placed in front of the normal eye, the eyes make a fusional vergence movement (both eyes move outward then refixate). When placed in front of the suppressing eye, no movement occurs — the suppression scotoma prevents the perception of diplopia that would drive refixation. Used to unmask microtropia in amblyopia with apparently aligned eyes.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe14',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Infantile esotropia (congenital esotropia) is associated with which ocular motility findings?',
options:['A. Alternating esotropia ~40-50 PD, normal ductions, latent nystagmus, inferior oblique overaction developing later','B. Small angle ET (<15 PD) with oblique overaction at onset','C. Constant exotropia that converts to esotropia','D. Restriction of adduction bilaterally','E. Normal eye alignment at 6 months with sudden onset ET at 18 months'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Infantile (congenital) esotropia: onset <6 months, large angle (30-50+ PD), alternating (cross-fixation), normal ductions (not a CN VI palsy), often with latent nystagmus (jerk nystagmus beating toward fixating eye), and inferior oblique overaction that develops around age 1-2 years. Associated: V-pattern, dissociated vertical deviation (DVD). Treatment: early surgical alignment (by 18-24 months) to optimize binocular development.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

{id:'pe15',subject:'pediatrics',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Retinoblastoma treatment in a child with advanced unilateral disease (group E) and no systemic spread is:',
options:['A. External beam radiation (EBRT)','B. Intravenous chemotherapy alone','C. Intra-arterial chemotherapy (IAC) as primary treatment','D. Enucleation with histopathological evaluation for high-risk features','E. Observation with frequent exams under anesthesia'],
correct:'D',
explanation:'Group E retinoblastoma (massive disease with >2/3 vitreous fill, iris NV, neo-glaucoma, or phthisis risk) has a very low chance of globe salvage. Enucleation (removal of the eye) is the safest treatment for unilateral Group E Rb without systemic spread, providing definitive histopathology for high-risk features (post-laminar optic nerve invasion, choroidal invasion >3 mm, scleral extension) that guide adjuvant chemotherapy decision-making. IAC is for earlier groups (B-D) in globe-salvage attempts.',
reference:'BCSC Section 6'},

// ── NEURO-OPHTHALMOLOGY ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'ne01',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A 35-year-old woman presents with painful monocular vision loss over 3 days, a relative afferent pupillary defect (RAPD), dyschromatopsia, and a cecocentral scotoma. MRI shows gadolinium enhancement of the optic nerve. The MOST likely diagnosis is:',
options:['A. Anterior ischemic optic neuropathy (AION)','B. Compressive optic neuropathy','C. Demyelinating optic neuritis','D. Leber hereditary optic neuropathy','E. Toxic/nutritional optic neuropathy'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'This is the classic presentation of demyelinating optic neuritis: young woman, painful eye movement, subacute vision loss, RAPD, color vision loss disproportionate to acuity, and MRI optic nerve enhancement. It is frequently associated with multiple sclerosis. The Optic Neuritis Treatment Trial (ONTT) showed IV methylprednisolone speeds recovery but does not improve final vision. AION is typically painless, older patients, altitudinal defect.',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne02',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'A patient with a right third nerve palsy has a completely blown pupil (dilated, non-reactive) and ptosis. The MOST URGENT next step is:',
options:['A. MRI with contrast of the orbits','B. CT angiography of the head (CTA) to rule out posterior communicating artery aneurysm','C. Thyroid function tests','D. Blood pressure measurement','E. Fasting blood glucose'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'A pupil-involving CN III palsy is a posterior communicating artery (PComm) aneurysm until proven otherwise. The aneurysm compresses the superficial pupillomotor fibers traveling on the outside of CN III. This is a neurosurgical emergency. CTA or MRA should be obtained immediately. Pupil-sparing CN III palsies in diabetic or hypertensive patients are more likely ischemic (microvascular, sparing the outer pupillomotor fibers).',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne03',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Horner syndrome includes which triad of findings?',
options:['A. Ptosis, miosis, anhidrosis (and reverse ptosis)','B. Ptosis, mydriasis, cycloplegia','C. Proptosis, ptosis, and ophthalmoplegia','D. Ptosis, miosis, and ophthalmoplegia','E. Miosis, cycloplegia, and brow ptosis'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Horner syndrome (oculosympathetic paresis) triad: (1) Ptosis (2-3 mm, due to loss of Muller muscle); (2) Miosis (pupil 1-2 mm smaller, more apparent in dim light); (3) Anhidrosis (ipsilateral face, if lesion is pre-ganglionic); (4) Reverse ptosis (lower lid elevation — "upside down ptosis" from inferior tarsal muscle denervation). No cycloplegia or ophthalmoplegia (those are CN III).',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne04',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Papilledema (bilateral disc edema from raised intracranial pressure) is distinguished from pseudopapilledema by:',
options:['A. Visual acuity is typically worse in papilledema','B. Spontaneous venous pulsations are preserved in papilledema','C. B-scan ultrasound shows optic nerve sheath dilation in papilledema','D. Fluorescein angiography shows disc leakage only in pseudopapilledema','E. Visual field testing is not useful in papilledema'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'B-scan ultrasound: in papilledema, the optic nerve sheath is distended by CSF (greater than 3 mm sheath width 3 mm behind the globe = positive "30-degree test"). FA: papilledema shows disc leakage/blurring of disc margins with staining; drusen (pseudopapilledema) may autofluoresce. SVP: if present, SVP argues against elevated ICP, but SVP is absent in 20% of normals. Acuity is often preserved in early papilledema.',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne05',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'The "one-and-a-half syndrome" results from a lesion in:',
options:['A. Bilateral CN VI nuclei','B. The ipsilateral CN III nucleus and MLF','C. The ipsilateral PPRF and ipsilateral MLF (or CN VI nucleus and MLF)','D. The contralateral PPRF only','E. The ipsilateral cerebellum'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'"One-and-a-half syndrome" = ipsilateral conjugate gaze palsy (the "one") + ipsilateral internuclear ophthalmoplegia (the "half"). Result: the only remaining horizontal movement is abduction of the contralateral eye (with nystagmus). Caused by a lesion at/near the ipsilateral PPRF (or CN VI nucleus — for the conjugate gaze) and the ipsilateral MLF (for the INO component). Classic cause: MS or pontine infarction.',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

// ── NEURO (continued) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'ne06',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient with pituitary macroadenoma presents with bitemporal hemianopia. The visual field defect corresponds to injury at which location?',
options:['A. Right optic tract','B. Left optic nerve','C. Optic chiasm, affecting the crossing nasal fibers','D. Both lateral geniculate bodies simultaneously','E. Left occipital cortex'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'The optic chiasm contains decussating nasal retinal fibers (carrying temporal visual field information). A pituitary adenoma compresses the chiasm inferiorly. The crossing nasal fibers (from both eyes) are interrupted → bitemporal hemianopia. The temporal fibers (nasal visual field) pass laterally through the chiasm and are not affected. Mnemonic: chiasm = crossing = temporal field loss.',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne07',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Which type of nystagmus is PATHOGNOMONIC for a posterior fossa (cerebellar/brainstem) lesion?',
options:['A. Pendular nystagmus','B. Jerk nystagmus with gaze evoked in both directions','C. Downbeat nystagmus in primary position','D. Latent nystagmus (only with monocular viewing)','E. Congenital nystagmus with null point'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Downbeat nystagmus (fast phase downward) in primary position is pathognomonic for a cervicomedullary junction lesion — Chiari malformation type I, cervicomedullary ischemia, demyelination, paraneoplastic syndrome, or lithium toxicity. It worsens on lateral gaze and with downgaze. Upbeat nystagmus in primary position indicates a pontomesencephalic or anterior vermis lesion. Latent nystagmus is a benign finding in infantile esotropia patients.',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne08',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A 40-year-old woman presents with headache and bilateral disc edema. MRI shows no mass. LP opening pressure is 35 cm H2O. The BEST initial treatment is:',
options:['A. Furosemide','B. Acetazolamide and weight loss (if overweight)','C. Lumboperitoneal shunt','D. Repeat LP every 2 weeks','E. IV dexamethasone'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH, pseudotumor cerebri): elevated ICP (>25 cm H2O) without mass or hydrocephalus, most common in obese women of childbearing age. First-line: acetazolamide (carbonic anhydrase inhibitor, reduces CSF production) + weight loss (the IIH Weight Trial showed weight loss equally effective). Serial LPs provide temporary relief. Optic nerve sheath fenestration or shunting for vision-threatening IIH. Topiramate is an alternative (appetite suppressant + CA inhibitor).',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne09',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'In a patient with right homonymous hemianopia (right half of visual field in both eyes), the lesion is located:',
options:['A. Right optic nerve','B. Optic chiasm','C. Left optic tract, lateral geniculate, or occipital cortex','D. Right occipital cortex','E. Right lateral geniculate body'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Homonymous hemianopia (same-sided field loss in both eyes) is a retrochiasmal lesion. Right homonymous hemianopia = loss of the right visual field in both eyes = left-sided retrochiasmal lesion (the left optic tract, LGB, optic radiation, or left occipital cortex). Rule: the lesion is CONTRALATERAL to the side of field loss. Incongruous homonymous hemianopia (asymmetric) = optic tract. Congruous (symmetric) = occipital cortex.',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne10',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'The ONTT (Optic Neuritis Treatment Trial) long-term follow-up showed which findings?',
options:['A. IV steroids improved final visual acuity compared to oral prednisone or observation','B. Oral prednisone was associated with increased risk of recurrent optic neuritis','C. Patients with MS at 5 years showed no difference regardless of initial treatment','D. Glatiramer acetate reduced conversion to MS in ONTT patients','E. All patients recovered to 20/40 or better regardless of treatment'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'ONTT key findings: (1) IV methylprednisolone speeded recovery but did NOT improve final VA (at 6 months, groups equalized). (2) Oral prednisone alone (1 mg/kg/day) was ASSOCIATED WITH INCREASED RISK of recurrent optic neuritis — the oral prednisone group was twice as likely to have recurrence. (3) High brain lesion burden on MRI at onset predicted conversion to MS. (4) 15-year ONTT: ~50% of patients with ≥1 MRI lesion at onset developed MS.',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne11',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The most common cause of an isolated CN IV (trochlear nerve) palsy in adults is:',
options:['A. Compressive (posterior fossa tumor)','B. Congenital trochlear nerve palsy','C. Microvascular (diabetic or hypertensive)','D. Trauma (closed head injury)','E. Multiple sclerosis demyelination'],
correct:'D',
explanation:'CN IV (trochlear nerve) palsy: the longest intracranial nerve and the only CN that exits dorsally (thus most susceptible to contrecoup forces). In adults: TRAUMA is the most common cause of acquired CN IV palsy (the nerve is vulnerable at the dorsal midbrain). In older patients with vascular risk factors: microvascular. CN IV palsy causes vertical diplopia worse on downgaze, contralateral head tilt (Parks-Bielschowsky 3-step test). Congenital CN IV palsy is often unmasked in adulthood by decompensation.',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne12',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'A patient presents with painful ophthalmoplegia, proptosis, and chemosis that developed over 2 days after a recent dental abscess. The MOST likely diagnosis is:',
options:['A. Thyroid eye disease flare','B. Orbital pseudotumor (idiopathic orbital inflammation)','C. Cavernous sinus thrombosis','D. CN III palsy from aneurysm','E. Tolosa-Hunt syndrome'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Septic cavernous sinus thrombosis (CST) classically follows facial infections (sinusitis, dental abscess, periorbital cellulitis). Bacteria spread via valveless facial veins retrograde to the cavernous sinus. Features: rapid onset, unilateral then bilateral proptosis, chemosis, ophthalmoplegia (CN III, IV, VI), CN V1/V2 sensory loss, septic fever, meningism. Treatment: IV antibiotics (MRSA coverage), anticoagulation (controversial), surgical drainage if source is identifiable. High mortality if untreated.',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne13',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Visual field testing in idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH) characteristically shows:',
options:['A. Bitemporal hemianopia from chiasmal compression','B. Enlarged blind spot and inferonasal visual field loss','C. Altitudinal field defect respecting the horizontal meridian','D. Centrocecal scotoma','E. Constricted field in all directions'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'IIH visual field defects reflect optic nerve damage from elevated ICP and disc edema. Most common: enlarged blind spot (earliest finding), followed by inferonasal arcuate defects, nasal step, and — in advanced cases — temporal or generalized constriction. Severe irreversible optic atrophy ("burnt-out IIH") causes constricted fields. Unlike pituitary adenoma (bitemporal) or optic neuritis (central scotoma), IIH does not cause bitemporal hemianopia.',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne14',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'An INO (internuclear ophthalmoplegia) on the LEFT side causes:',
options:['A. Failure of the left eye to abduct','B. Failure of the left eye to adduct with contralateral abducting nystagmus','C. Bilateral gaze palsy','D. Right gaze palsy','E. Vertical diplopia only'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'INO = interruption of the MLF (medial longitudinal fasciculus) between the CN VI nucleus (abducens, controlling horizontal gaze) and CN III nucleus (oculomotor, controlling medial rectus). Left INO: left MLF lesion → left medial rectus gets no signal during rightward gaze → left eye fails to adduct + right eye shows abducting nystagmus (dissociated nystagmus). Convergence is preserved (uses a separate pathway). Most common cause in young adults: MS. In elderly: brainstem infarction.',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

{id:'ne15',subject:'neuro',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Giant cell arteritis (GCA) causing anterior ischemic optic neuropathy (AION) primarily affects which vessel?',
options:['A. Central retinal artery','B. Posterior ciliary arteries (short PCAs) supplying the optic nerve head','C. Ophthalmic artery directly','D. Intraocular arterioles','E. Choroidal arteries of the peripapillary region only'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Arteritic AION (A-AION, caused by GCA): granulomatous inflammation affects medium-sized arteries, particularly the short posterior ciliary arteries (SPCAs) that supply the optic nerve head (prelaminar and laminar portions) via the circle of Zinn-Haller. Ischemic infarction of the optic nerve head causes sudden, painless, severe vision loss with an altitudinal VF defect and pale disc edema. ESR, CRP, and platelet count should be checked; treatment: urgent high-dose IV corticosteroids (do NOT wait for biopsy).',
reference:'BCSC Section 5'},

// ── UVEITIS ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'uv01',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'A 28-year-old HLA-B27-positive male with ankylosing spondylitis develops acute onset of unilateral eye pain, photophobia, and a hypopyon. The MOST likely diagnosis is:',
options:['A. Posterior uveitis','B. Anterior uveitis (iritis/iridocyclitis)','C. Behcet disease','D. Sarcoidosis','E. Toxoplasma retinochoroiditis'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'HLA-B27-associated uveitis is the classic cause of acute anterior uveitis. Features: acute onset, unilateral (alternating attacks), severe photophobia/pain, significant fibrin/hypopyon, and association with seronegative spondyloarthropathies (AS, Reiter syndrome, IBD-associated, psoriatic arthritis). Treatment: intensive topical steroids and cycloplegics. Behcet can also cause hypopyon uveitis but is HLA-B51 and typically bilateral with other systemic features.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv02',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The "headlight in the fog" appearance on fundus exam describes:',
options:['A. Active toxoplasma retinochoroiditis adjacent to an old scar','B. Acute retinal necrosis (ARN)','C. Cytomegalovirus (CMV) retinitis in an immunocompromised patient','D. Birdshot chorioretinopathy','E. Presumed ocular histoplasmosis syndrome (POHS)'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'"Headlight in the fog" describes a white, fluffy active toxoplasma lesion adjacent to a pigmented, punched-out old chorioretinal scar — the active lesion (headlight) surrounded by overlying vitritis (the fog). Toxoplasma gondii is the most common cause of posterior uveitis worldwide. The active lesion arises from cyst reactivation at the edge of an old scar.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv03',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Sympathetic ophthalmia (SO) is a bilateral granulomatous uveitis that occurs after:',
options:['A. Autoimmune attack triggered by viral uveitis in one eye','B. Penetrating trauma or surgery to one eye, with subsequent uveal tissue sensitization','C. Systemic sarcoidosis with bilateral ocular involvement','D. Herpes zoster affecting both CN V divisions simultaneously','E. Behcet disease with bilateral ocular inflammation'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Sympathetic ophthalmia is a rare (less than 0.3% after penetrating trauma) bilateral granulomatous panuveitis that develops in the uninjured (sympathizing) eye weeks to months after penetrating injury or surgery to the other (exciting) eye. Proposed mechanism: T-cell sensitization to uveal antigens (melanin-associated antigens). Treatment: systemic immunosuppression (high-dose steroids, steroid-sparing agents). Enucleation of the exciting eye within 2 weeks of injury may prevent SO.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv04',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Sarcoid uveitis MOST commonly presents as:',
options:['A. Acute anterior uveitis','B. Chronic granulomatous anterior uveitis with mutton-fat keratic precipitates','C. Acute posterior uveitis with exudative detachment','D. Vitritis only without anterior segment involvement','E. Isolated optic nerve granuloma'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Ocular sarcoidosis most commonly causes chronic, bilateral, granulomatous anterior uveitis with large "mutton-fat" keratic precipitates (KPs), iris nodules (Koeppe at pupillary margin, Busacca in stroma), and posterior synechiae. It may also cause intermediate uveitis (snowballs/snowbanking), periphlebitis ("candle wax drippings"), optic disc granulomas. Workup: ACE level, lysozyme, chest CT/X-ray.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

// ── UVEITIS (continued) ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'uv05',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Intermediate uveitis (pars planitis) is MOST commonly associated with:',
options:['A. HLA-B27 and ankylosing spondylitis','B. Multiple sclerosis and sarcoidosis','C. Toxoplasma and CMV','D. Behcet disease','E. Juvenile idiopathic arthritis'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Intermediate uveitis affects the vitreous, pars plana, and peripheral retina. "Pars planitis" = the idiopathic subset. Associated systemic diseases: multiple sclerosis (in ~15%) and sarcoidosis. Presentation: floaters ("floaters galore"), vitreous cells, "snowballs" (vitreous aggregates), and "snowbanking" (pars plana exudate). Complications: cystoid macular edema (main cause of vision loss), cataract. Treatment: periocular or systemic steroids, immunosuppression, vitrectomy for advanced CME or snowbanking.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv06',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'The HLA type most strongly associated with uveitis in Behcet disease is:',
options:['A. HLA-B27','B. HLA-B51','C. HLA-DR4','D. HLA-A29','E. HLA-B7'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Behcet disease is strongly associated with HLA-B51 (particularly in Middle Eastern and Asian patients from the Silk Road). Behcet uveitis: bilateral, recurrent, non-granulomatous panuveitis with hypopyon (layered pus without fibrin in AC), retinal vasculitis, and posterior segment involvement. It is a systemic vasculitis — oral and genital ulcers, skin lesions (erythema nodosum, pathergy). HLA-B27 is associated with seronegative spondylarthropathy-related anterior uveitis. HLA-A29 is associated with birdshot chorioretinopathy.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv07',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Fuchs heterochromic iridocyclitis (FHI) is characterized by:',
options:['A. Acute anterior uveitis with hypopyon','B. Chronic low-grade anterior uveitis with stellate KPs, iris heterochromia, no posterior synechiae, and association with cataract/glaucoma','C. Granulomatous anterior uveitis with mutton-fat KPs','D. Bilateral severe uveitis with exudative retinal detachment','E. Association with HLA-B27 and spondylarthropathy'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'FHI features: unilateral, diffuse stellate (star-shaped) KPs distributed over the entire endothelium (not concentrated inferiorly), iris atrophy causing heterochromia (lighter eye is affected), NO posterior synechiae (a hallmark — posterior synechiae exclude FHI), minimal symptoms, fine rubeosis, and association with Toxoplasma seropositivity and rubella virus in the aqueous. Complications: cataract (>90%) and glaucoma (~20%). Does NOT respond dramatically to steroids.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv08',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Posterior uveitis caused by Toxoplasma gondii is treated with:',
options:['A. Acyclovir and topical steroids','B. Pyrimethamine + sulfadiazine + leucovorin (classic regimen) or trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole','C. Topical antifungal agents','D. Natamycin 5% drops','E. IV ganciclovir'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Active toxoplasma retinochoroiditis (large lesion >0.5 DD, threatening macula/optic nerve, or in immunocompromised) is treated with antiparasitic therapy: classic regimen = pyrimethamine + sulfadiazine + leucovorin (folinic acid to prevent bone marrow suppression). Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole (TMP-SMX) is equally effective and better tolerated. Clindamycin + sulfadiazine is another option. Adjunctive systemic corticosteroids (after starting antiparasitic) reduce inflammation around the macula or nerve.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv09',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Birdshot chorioretinopathy is associated with which HLA type and has which characteristic angiographic finding?',
options:['A. HLA-A29; multiple scattered, cream-colored choroidal lesions with disc and macular leakage on FA','B. HLA-B27; snowbanking on fluorescein angiography','C. HLA-DR4; geographic atrophy on FA','D. HLA-B51; punched-out chorioretinal scars on FA','E. HLA-B7; multifocal pigment epithelial detachments'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Birdshot chorioretinopathy: one of the strongest HLA-disease associations in uveitis — HLA-A29 in >95% of patients. Bilateral, posterior uveitis with minimal anterior involvement, scattered cream-colored ovoid choroidal lesions radiating from the disc, minimal vitritis, and retinal vasculitis. FA/ICGA show multiple hypofluorescent choroidal lesions. ERG is typically abnormal (b-wave reduction). Associations: CME, ERM, optic atrophy, CNV. Treatment: systemic immunosuppression (mycophenolate, cyclosporine).',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv10',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'A patient with uveitis has a positive ACE and chest CT showing bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy. The BEST confirmatory test for sarcoidosis-related uveitis is:',
options:['A. Serum lysozyme level','B. Gallium scan showing "panda" and "lambda" signs','C. Tissue biopsy showing non-caseating granulomas','D. Positive Kveim test','E. Positive Mantoux (PPD) skin test'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'Definitive diagnosis of sarcoidosis requires histopathologic evidence of non-caseating granulomas from tissue biopsy (lung, conjunctiva, lacrimal gland, lymph node — most accessible sites). ACE and lysozyme are elevated in ~60-75% of active sarcoidosis but are not specific. Gallium scan (panda = parotid/lacrimal gland uptake, lambda = hilar LN uptake) is suggestive. The Kveim test is obsolete. PPD is often negative in sarcoidosis (anergy).',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv11',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Juvenile idiopathic arthritis (JIA)-associated uveitis most commonly presents as:',
options:['A. Acute symptomatic anterior uveitis in a boy with HLA-B27','B. Chronic, insidious, bilateral asymptomatic anterior uveitis in a girl with oligoarticular JIA who is ANA-positive','C. Posterior uveitis with snowballs','D. Panuveitis with systemic features','E. Acute red painful eye with hypopyon'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'JIA-associated uveitis: most common in oligoarticular JIA in young girls who are ANA-positive. It is typically ASYMPTOMATIC (no pain, redness, or photophobia initially) — hence the importance of routine screening. Findings: anterior uveitis with band keratopathy, posterior synechiae, cataract, and glaucoma from chronic inflammation and steroid treatment. Screening: every 3 months for 4 years (highest risk group: ANA+, oligoarticular, <6 years onset). The silent uveitis causes permanent damage if not detected.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv12',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The MOST common cause of posterior uveitis WORLDWIDE is:',
options:['A. Cytomegalovirus retinitis','B. Toxoplasmosis (Toxoplasma gondii)','C. Tuberculosis','D. Syphilis','E. Candida endophthalmitis'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Toxoplasmosis is the most common cause of posterior uveitis worldwide, accounting for approximately 30-50% of all posterior uveitis in immunocompetent patients in most series. It is caused by Toxoplasma gondii (an obligate intracellular parasite). The characteristic lesion is a fluffy white-yellow necrotizing retinochoroiditis adjacent to an old pigmented scar ("headlight in the fog"). CMV retinitis is the most common cause in immunocompromised (HIV/AIDS) patients.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv13',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'Band keratopathy (calcium deposition in the cornea) in the setting of chronic uveitis is treated with:',
options:['A. Topical steroids to reduce inflammation','B. EDTA chelation with superficial keratectomy','C. Corneal transplantation','D. Nd:YAG laser photodisruption','E. Lubricating drops only'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Band keratopathy is calcium hydroxyapatite deposition in the superficial corneal stroma and Bowman layer, forming a band across the interpalpebral zone. Treatment: superficial keratectomy under topical anesthesia + EDTA (ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid) solution applied to chelate and dissolve the calcium. The calcium literally fizzes off. PTK can smooth the surface afterward. Causes: chronic ocular inflammation (JIA uveitis is classic), hypercalcemia (hyperparathyroidism, sarcoidosis), silicone oil, chronic corneal edema.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv14',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Cytomegalovirus (CMV) retinitis in HIV/AIDS is treated with which first-line agent?',
options:['A. Acyclovir IV','B. Foscarnet IV','C. Ganciclovir IV or valganciclovir orally','D. Cidofovir IV only','E. Intravitreal methotrexate'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'CMV retinitis management: induction therapy with IV ganciclovir or oral valganciclovir (a prodrug of ganciclovir with excellent oral bioavailability), followed by maintenance therapy. Intravitreal ganciclovir implant (Vitrasert) provides high local drug levels. Foscarnet and cidofovir are used for ganciclovir-resistant cases. Most importantly: initiate antiretroviral therapy (ART) to restore CD4 count — the retinitis will eventually become inactive with immune reconstitution (watch for immune recovery uveitis).',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

{id:'uv15',subject:'uveitis',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Which biologic medication is used to treat refractory non-infectious uveitis, and works by inhibiting TNF-alpha?',
options:['A. Methotrexate','B. Adalimumab (Humira)','C. Mycophenolate mofetil','D. Rituximab (anti-CD20)','E. Voclosporin'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Adalimumab (Humira), a monoclonal anti-TNF-alpha antibody, is FDA-approved for non-infectious intermediate, posterior, and panuveitis in adults (VISUAL I and II trials, 2016) — the first biologic approved for uveitis. It significantly reduced treatment failure rates vs. placebo when added to conventional immunosuppression. Infliximab (another anti-TNF) is used off-label and is preferred for Behcet disease-associated uveitis. Methotrexate and mycophenolate are steroid-sparing first-line agents but are not biologics.',
reference:'BCSC Section 9'},

// ── BASIC SCIENCE & ANATOMY ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'bs01',subject:'basic',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The fovea centralis has the highest density of which photoreceptors?',
options:['A. Rods only','B. Both rods and cones equally','C. Cones only (no rods in the foveal center)','D. Rods in the center, cones in the parafovea','E. Intrinsically photosensitive retinal ganglion cells'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'The fovea centralis (specifically the foveola, ~350 um central zone) contains exclusively cone photoreceptors — there are NO rods in the central foveola. The rods begin at the edge of the fovea (~1 degree from fixation) and peak in density at ~20 degrees eccentricity (nasal to fovea). This is why rod-mediated (scotopic) vision is best with averted (eccentric) gaze — "off-axis fixation."',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs02',subject:'basic',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The blood-retinal barrier (BRB) consists of:',
options:['A. Tight junctions between retinal pigment epithelial cells and between retinal vascular endothelial cells','B. The internal limiting membrane and Bruch\'s membrane','C. The ganglion cell layer and the RPE','D. Tight junctions only at the retinal capillaries','E. The vitreous base and zonular fibers'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'The blood-retinal barrier has two components: (1) OUTER BRB: tight junctions (zonulae occludens) between RPE cells, preventing diffusion from choriocapillaris into outer retina; (2) INNER BRB: tight junctions between retinal vascular endothelial cells, preventing intravascular contents from entering the inner retina. Breakdown of either component leads to retinal edema.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs03',subject:'basic',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'The visual cycle (phototransduction) ends with the regeneration of 11-cis-retinal. Where does this regeneration primarily occur?',
options:['A. In the photoreceptor outer segment itself','B. In the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE)','C. In the Muller cells for cone photoreceptors','D. In the interphotoreceptor matrix','E. In the inner segments of photoreceptors'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'After photoisomerization, all-trans-retinal is released from opsin, reduced to all-trans-retinol (vitamin A) in the outer segment, transported to the RPE, and re-isomerized to 11-cis-retinol then oxidized to 11-cis-retinal, then returned to the photoreceptor for regeneration of rhodopsin. This "visual cycle" or "retinoid cycle" requires RPE65 (a key isomerase). Cone photoreceptors can also use an alternative Muller cell pathway for faster regeneration.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs04',subject:'basic',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The ciliary body produces aqueous humor. Which of the following CORRECTLY describes aqueous outflow?',
options:['A. 90% uveoscleral, 10% trabecular','B. 80-90% trabecular (conventional), 10-20% uveoscleral (unconventional)','C. 50% trabecular, 50% uveoscleral','D. 100% through the trabecular meshwork','E. 80% through Schlemm\'s canal directly, 20% trabecular'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Conventional (trabecular) outflow: ~80-90% of aqueous drains through the trabecular meshwork → Schlemm\'s canal → collector channels → episcleral veins. Unconventional (uveoscleral) outflow: ~10-20% flows through the ciliary muscle interstitium → suprachoroidal space → sclera. Prostaglandin analogues (latanoprost, etc.) primarily increase UVEOSCLERAL outflow. Beta-blockers reduce aqueous production.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs05',subject:'basic',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The cranial nerve responsible for the corneal blink reflex (afferent limb) is:',
options:['A. CN II (optic nerve)','B. CN V1 (ophthalmic division of trigeminal)','C. CN VII (facial nerve)','D. CN III (oculomotor nerve)','E. CN VI (abducens nerve)'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The corneal blink reflex: AFFERENT = nasociliary branch of V1 (CN V ophthalmic division) carrying sensation from the cornea; EFFERENT = CN VII (facial nerve) causing orbicularis oculi contraction → eye closure. Testing: touch cornea → both eyes should blink (direct and consensual). Loss of afferent (V1 lesion): no blink in either eye when that cornea is touched. Loss of efferent (CN VII palsy): no blink in the ipsilateral eye regardless of which cornea is stimulated.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs06',subject:'basic',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Optical coherence tomography (OCT) of the macula uses which principle?',
options:['A. Ultrasound with B-scan technology at 20 MHz','B. Low-coherence interferometry with near-infrared light','C. Confocal scanning laser ophthalmoscopy','D. Scanning laser polarimetry','E. Scanning laser doppler flowmetry'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'OCT uses low-coherence interferometry: a near-infrared light beam (~840 nm for time-domain; ~1060 nm for long-wavelength) is split — one beam goes to the tissue, one to a reference mirror. Backscattered light from the tissue interferes with the reference beam; the interference pattern encodes depth information. Spectral-domain OCT measures all depths simultaneously via Fourier transform, giving axial resolution ~5-7 um.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs07',subject:'basic',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Which cytokine is the PRIMARY driver of corneal neovascularization?',
options:['A. IL-1 beta','B. VEGF-A (vascular endothelial growth factor A)','C. TNF-alpha','D. TGF-beta','E. IL-17'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'VEGF-A (specifically isoforms VEGF-A165 and VEGF-A121) is the primary angiogenic factor driving new vessel growth, including corneal neovascularization, retinal neovascularization in PDR/ROP, and choroidal neovascularization in AMD. VEGF binds VEGFR-1 and VEGFR-2 on endothelial cells, driving proliferation, migration, and survival. This is the target of anti-VEGF drugs (bevacizumab, ranibizumab, aflibercept). IL-1 beta plays a role in corneal inflammation and NV but is not the primary driver.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2/8'},

// ── BASIC SCIENCE (continued) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
{id:'bs08',subject:'basic',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The choroid receives its blood supply primarily from:',
options:['A. Central retinal artery branches','B. Short posterior ciliary arteries (SPCAs) from the ophthalmic artery','C. Long posterior ciliary arteries (LPCAs)','D. Anterior ciliary arteries','E. Muscular branches of the ophthalmic artery'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The choroid (the highly vascularized uveal layer) is supplied primarily by the SHORT posterior ciliary arteries (SPCAs), branches of the ophthalmic artery that pierce the sclera around the optic nerve. The LPCAs (2 total) supply the anterior uveal tract (iris, ciliary body) and form the major arterial circle of the iris. The choriocapillaris supplies the outer retina (photoreceptors) via diffusion across the RPE and Bruch membrane.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs09',subject:'basic',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'The PERG (pattern electroretinogram) specifically reflects the function of:',
options:['A. Rod photoreceptors','B. Cone photoreceptors only','C. Macular ganglion cells and inner retina','D. RPE function','E. Retinal blood vessels'],
correct:'C',
explanation:'The PERG (pattern ERG) uses a reversing checkerboard pattern to selectively drive central (macular) retina. The response (N95 and P50 components) reflects macular ganglion cell function — specifically the N95 component is generated by retinal ganglion cells. It is used to differentiate macular disease (P50 reduced) from optic nerve disease (N95 reduced with relatively preserved P50). The flash ERG reflects peripheral photoreceptor function; the mfERG maps retinal topography.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs10',subject:'basic',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'Accommodation is driven by contraction of the ciliary muscle, which:',
options:['A. Stretches the zonules, flattening the lens','B. Releases zonular tension, allowing the elastic lens capsule to make the lens more spherical','C. Directly compresses the lens equator to increase power','D. Increases vitreous pressure to push the lens anteriorly','E. Constricts the pupil to increase depth of focus'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'Accommodation (Helmholtz theory): ciliary muscle contracts → ciliary ring moves anteriorly and inward → zonular fibers relax → the inherently elastic lens capsule molds the lens into a more spherical (more convex) shape → increased dioptric power (near focus). Presbyopia results from progressive loss of lens elasticity (not primarily ciliary muscle weakness). The Schachar theory (stretching via zonules) is the main alternative but is not the currently accepted mainstream mechanism.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs11',subject:'basic',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The macula lutea gets its yellow color from:',
options:['A. Lipofuscin accumulation in the RPE','B. Xanthophyll pigments (lutein and zeaxanthin) in the inner retinal layers','C. Melanin in the RPE','D. Hemoglobin in the perifoveal capillaries','E. Lipid deposits in Henle fiber layer'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The yellow pigment of the macula comes from xanthophyll carotenoids — specifically lutein and zeaxanthin — concentrated in the inner plexiform layer, nerve fiber layer, and (especially) the photoreceptor axons (Henle fiber layer) at the fovea. They act as blue light filters and antioxidants, protecting the photoreceptors. The fovea is yellow only when viewed with a red-free (green) filter. Low macular pigment optical density (MPOD) may increase AMD risk.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs12',subject:'basic',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Which statement about the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) is MOST accurate?',
options:['A. RPE cells can regenerate rapidly after injury','B. RPE functions include phagocytosis of shed outer segment discs, vitamin A processing, ion transport, and forming the outer BRB','C. RPE is derived from the neural crest','D. RPE does not contribute to the blood-retinal barrier','E. Each RPE cell is associated with approximately 1 photoreceptor'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'RPE functions (critical for photoreceptor survival): (1) Daily phagocytosis of shed outer segment membrane discs (~10% of outer segment shed daily); (2) Visual cycle — isomerization of all-trans-retinol to 11-cis-retinal (requires RPE65); (3) Outer blood-retinal barrier (tight junctions); (4) Ion/fluid transport (subretinal fluid clearance); (5) Growth factor support. Each RPE cell supports ~30 photoreceptors. RPE is derived from the neuroectoderm (optic cup outer layer), not neural crest.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs13',subject:'basic',difficulty:'medium',
stem:'The crystalline lens of the human eye is avascular and receives nutrients via:',
options:['A. Diffusion from the anterior vitreous humor','B. Diffusion from the aqueous humor (both anterior and posterior compartments)','C. Diffusion from the choroidal vasculature through the zonules','D. Lens vasculature from the hyaloid artery remnant','E. Direct neural supply from the ciliary nerves'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The lens is entirely avascular after birth (the hyaloid artery regresses in utero). Nutrients (glucose, amino acids, antioxidants) diffuse from the aqueous humor. Glucose metabolism is primarily anaerobic (glycolysis) due to limited oxygen supply. The lens uses the hexose monophosphate shunt and glutathione system to counteract oxidative stress. Disruption of these pathways leads to cataract (e.g., galactose cataract in galactosemia, "sugar" cataracts in diabetes via aldose reductase/sorbitol pathway).',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs14',subject:'basic',difficulty:'easy',
stem:'The optic nerve contains approximately how many retinal ganglion cell axons?',
options:['A. 100,000','B. 1 million (1.2 million)','C. 5 million','D. 120 million','E. 6 million'],
correct:'B',
explanation:'The optic nerve contains approximately 1.0-1.2 million retinal ganglion cell (RGC) axons. The retina contains ~120 million rod photoreceptors and ~6 million cones, converging via bipolar and amacrine cells onto ~1.2 million ganglion cells. Significant convergence (120:1 for rods in peripheral retina) vs. near 1:1 at the fovea (each foveal cone has its own midget ganglion cell pathway). Loss of 20-40% of nerve fibers can occur before VF loss is detectable by standard perimetry.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},

{id:'bs15',subject:'basic',difficulty:'hard',
stem:'Phototransduction cascade: after rhodopsin (Rh) absorbs a photon, the CORRECT sequence is:',
options:['A. Rh* activates Gt (transducin) → PDE activation → cGMP decreases → CNG channels close → hyperpolarization','B. Rh* activates Gi → adenylyl cyclase → cAMP decreases → K+ channels close → depolarization','C. Rh* activates PKC → IP3 release → Ca2+ release → GABA release','D. Rh* activates PLC directly → DAG increases → Na+ influx → depolarization','E. Rh* activates arrestin → opsin phosphorylation → all-trans-retinal release only'],
correct:'A',
explanation:'Phototransduction: (1) Photon isomerizes 11-cis-retinal to all-trans-retinal → rhodopsin activates (Rh*); (2) Rh* activates Gt (transducin, a Gi-type G-protein); (3) Gt-alpha activates phosphodiesterase (PDE6); (4) PDE hydrolyzes cGMP → cGMP levels fall; (5) Cyclic nucleotide-gated (CNG) channels close (less Na+ and Ca2+ influx); (6) Photoreceptor hyperpolarizes (dark current stops); (7) Reduced glutamate release to bipolar cells. Arrestin terminates the activated Rh*.',
reference:'BCSC Section 2'},
];
